<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka, Norway Sign Deal On Deportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 4 (Xinhua) - Sri Lanka and Norway have signed an
agreement under which the Scandinavian country would deport Sri
Lankans who do not have valid authorization of residency, the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"This agreement signals Norway's intention to repatriate failed
asylum-seekers and reflects the improvement in the human rights
situation in Sri Lanka," the ministry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Sri Lankans, mostly minority Tamils, leave their
war-torn country every year to seek asylum in Europe due to the
ongoing ethnic war between government troops and the Liberation
Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) who have been fighting a war for a
separate homeland for minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and
east for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
Norway has been host to a sizeable Sri Lankan Tamil expatriate
or refugee population since the war started in 1983.
</P>
<P>
Norway, having carved a niche for itself in resolving
international conflicts, said earlier this year that it would work
to bring the government and the LTTE to the negotiating table in
an attempt to end the bloody war which has claimed more than 55,
000 lives.
</P>
<P>
The deportation deal came as Germany was speeding procedures to
deport some 5,500 Sri Lankan nationals whose asylum requests had
been rejected.
</P>
<P>
Last month, 20 Sri Lankans were sent back to Colombo from
Germany on a special flight chartered by the German government.
</P>
<P>
German embassy officials here said another Sri Lankan national
is expected to be deported on Thursday by Germany which with some
60,000 people of Sri Lankan origin deported 150 people last year
in small numbers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
