<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Iraqi Accusations of Mistreating POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry spokesman
Hamid Reza Asefi on Wednesday dismissed as groundless an Iraqi
claim that Iraqi prisoners of war (POWs) are mistreated in Iran.
</P>
<P>
Despite the clear evidence showing Iranian POW's being
mistreated in Iraqi camps, Iran has always adopted the most humane
and respectful behavior toward Iraqi prisoners held in the country,
Asefi was quoted by the Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein recently accused Iran of
mistreating Iraqi POWs held since the bloody war from 1980 to 1988
which killed about 1 million people, IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
At a time when Iran is on the brink of releasing a large number
of Iraqi POWs, the Iraqi president made such baseless accusations,
Asefi regretted.
</P>
<P>
He said as a humanitarian action and a sign of good will, Iran
in cooperation with the International Committee of the Red Cross is
going to set free 2,000 Iraqi POWs next Friday.
</P>
<P>
The obstructive measures taken by Iraqi authorities have
protracted the process of swapping the POWs, he added.
</P>
<P>
He called on the Iraqi government to take an appropriate
initiative in solving the issue of POWs of both countries instead
of leveling baseless allegations.
</P>
<P>
Iran claimed last month that Iraq still holds 2,800 Iranians
according to available documents, in spite of the Iraqi claim that
it has repatriated all Iranian POWs.
</P>
<P>
Last August, Iranian officials said that Iran had released 55,
438 Iraqi POWs since 1981 on 103 occasions while Iraq had freed 39,
417 Iranian POWs in the same period on 70 occasions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
