<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0009 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Turkish Ruling Coalition Backs Away From Presidency Extension (By Xing Guoxin, Huai Chengbo) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish coalition government
later Wednesday gave up a constitutional reform bill aimed to
extend President Suleyman Demirel's term in office after it failed
to pass the parliament for a second time in the day.
</P>
<P>
The coalition government decided to withdrawal the bill, which
called for reducing the presidential tenure from seven years to
five years but allowing for re-election, before a third and final
vote.
</P>
<P>
The bill, promoted by Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit's ruling
coalition, suffered another defeat in the second vote with only 303
deputies' approval, the same as the score seven days ago.
</P>
<P>
A minimum of 330 votes in the 550-seat parliament are required
for the legislature's approval of any constitutional amendment
proposal and 367 votes are needed to secure the adoption of the
proposal without a national referendum.
</P>
<P>
Like what happened seven days ago, the defeat was largely due to
defections of many deputies from Ecevit's ruling partner Motherland
Party who have been against the extension of president's tenure.
</P>
<P>
Before the voting, Ecevit called on maverick deputies to cast
their secret votes in open to back up their promise to pave the way
for Demirel's re-election.
</P>
<P>
The result indicated, however, some 100 deputies of the ruling
parties voted against the bill, probably the same as those who
voted against it in the secret ballot last week despite their
earlier written endorsement.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit had argued that the re-election of Demirel, whose tenure
expires on May 16, was crucial for the stability in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister feared that dissent among ruling parties over
Demirel's successor could hamper the government's economic reform
package and much-needed political stability at a time when Turkey
is striving for membership of the European Union.
</P>
<P>
Demirel has failed to draw enough support from the deputies who
say that the country's political stability cannot be linked to one
old person and that it is time for him to retire from politics.
</P>
<P>
Demirel, 76, has been active in Turkish politics for almost 40
years. Many see him as the symbol of immobility in Turkish politics
and favor new faces.
</P>
<P>
The ruling parties said Monday after a meeting of leaders of the
three coalition partners that failure to pass the constitutional
amendment will not represent a crisis for the government.
</P>
<P>
But analysts said that the coalition partners will face a
different problem as the search for a new president candidate
begins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
