<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNTR Critical for U.S. Business and Workers, Chamber Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States Chamber of
Commerce said on Wednesday that the Clinton administration's trade
deal with China is "critical" to American businesses and workers,
and Congressmen should pass Permanent Normal Trade Relations (PNTR)
when it comes up for a vote late this year.
</P>
<P>
"This vote is not about politics it's about paychecks. PNTR
for China means more jobs at better wages for American workers,"
said Bruce Josten, Chamber Executive Vice President.
</P>
<P>
"A vote against PNTR is a vote against giving American
businesses, workers and farmers access to 1.2 billion Chinese
consumers," he added.
</P>
<P>
China and the United States reached an agreement on WTO last
November, which would lower China's trade tariffs dramatically and
open its telecommunications, insurance, banking and securities
markets for the first time to foreign competitors.
</P>
<P>
"China will enter the World Trade Organization without regard
to our action on their trading status, but unless we grant China
PNTR, we will not receive the benefits of our own trade agreement
 but our foreign competitors will," Josten said.
</P>
<P>
Recent surveys show that the trade deal would boost annual U.S.
exports by roughly 13 billion U.S. dollars in five years and
increase agricultural exports by 2.2 billion per year.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Chamber of Commerce, the world's largest business
federation representing more than three million businesses and
organizations, has launched a nationwide grassroots initiative,
Trade Roots, to educate local leaders and the public about the
importance of international trade to local communities. Trade
Roots currently is working hard to mobilize support for U.S.-China
WTO agreement and the PNTR vote.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the National Association of Manufacturers (NAM) on
Wednesday lauded House Speaker Dennis Hastert for scheduling a
vote on China PNTR for the week of May 22, calling it "a smart and
critical step".
</P>
<P>
"The speaker's leadership in putting this historic vote above
partisan politics is very important to getting China PNTR through
the House," and "holding the vote that week will enable us to
build bipartisan support before the turmoil of the election season
takes over," NAM President Jerry Jasinowski said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that Congressional passage of PNTR is of great concern
to America's manufacturers, particularly NAM's small- and medium-
sized firms which account for 82 percent of U.S. companies that
export to China.
</P>
<P>
"Without PNTR, the more open trade that China has promised will
not be available to the thousands of U.S. manufacturers and
employees who want to sell into this market," Jasinowski said on
Monday at a NAM news conference with House Majority leader Dick
Armey.
</P>
<P>
That market, however, will be open to America's competitors in
Europe and Japan, he added.
</P>
<P>
The NAM is America's largest and oldest multi-industry trade
association, composed of 14,000 members, including 10,000 small-
and mid-sized companies, and 350 member associations serving
manufacturers and employees in every industrial sector and all 50
states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
