<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mandelson Urges IRA to Show Positive Signs on Arms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Northern Ireland
Secretary Peter Mandelson said on Wednesday that he hoped for
progress in the peace process by Easter (April 23).
</P>
<P>
He told the British parliament's Northern Ireland Select
Committee that the British and Irish governments, co-sponsors of
the peace process, were working hard to come up with some sort of
blueprint to help get the province's stalled peace process back on
track.
</P>
<P>
"I think it might be possible...to elicit a response from the
IRA in the coming weeks. But I don't think Easter will be the
finishing line for those discussions," Mandelson said.
</P>
<P>
"The issue of decommissioning must be addressed," Mandelson
said. "People still live under the threat of violence. The guns
may be silent but they have not yet been put beyond use.
</P>
<P>
He also admitted that the prospects for full decommissioning by
May 22 were poor.
</P>
<P>
In Belfast, pro-British Protestant leader David Trimble warned
that if the arms impasse was not soon resolved, political progress
in Northern Ireland could be delayed for years.
</P>
<P>
Trimble told an Ulster Unionist women's conference on Wednesday
he believed the opportunity for progress still existed, but would
not remain for long.
</P>
<P>
The April 1998 Good Friday peace Agreement could go into cold
storage if there is no movement on the arms issue, he added.
</P>
<P>
"If we don't resolve differences before May 22 or before the
summer, then we are going to have problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Unless the decommissioning (disarmament) issue is resolved
with clarity and certainty in the next few weeks, I fear the
chances of political agreement in Northern Ireland might be
postponed for several years," Trimble told the conference.
</P>
<P>
The province's move away from 30 years of sectarian violence to
a lasting peace has stumbled since Mandelson suspended a fledgling
power-sharing executive in February.
</P>
<P>
Britain said the Irish Republican Army's failure to give a
clear commitment to hand in arms in line with the landmark Good
Friday peace agreement left it with no choice.
</P>
<P>
London and Dublin are struggling to find ways of reviving the
political institutions by May 22, which the 1998 agreement set as
the date for a completion of an arms handover.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Mitchel McLaughlin and Bairbre de
Brun from Sinn Fein, the political wing of IRA, will lead a
delegation to lobby MPs in London on Thursday ahead of a half-day
Westminster debate on the reform of the Royal Ulster Constabulary
(RUC).
</P>
<P>
An Ulster Unionist motion will be debated which urges the
British government to retain the RUC name and symbols and attempt
to persuade it to postpone the sweeping reforms recommended in the
Patten Report on future of policing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
