<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 91 NAMC Countries to Meet in Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BOGOTA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Until now, 91 countries out of 115
from the Non-Aligned Movement Countries (NAMC) have confirmed
their assistance at the movement's 8th ministerial conference to
take place on April 8 and 9 at Cartagena, in northern Colombia.
</P>
<P>
According to Colombia's Foreign Ministry, seven multilateral
organisms will be present in Cartagena from Saturday for a
conference at which the progress and application of the NAMC's
mandate set in Durban, South Africa, will be studied. In Durban,
Colombia handed over this organism's presidency to the African
country.
</P>
<P>
The group of multilateral entities to participate in the
ministerial conference is made up, in part, by the United Nations:
the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), the U.N.
Education, Science and Culture Organization (UNESCO) and the U.N.
Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO); the International Red
Cross Committee (IRCC); the Asian and African Peoples Society
Organization (AAPS); and the Committee for the Inalienable Rights
of the Palestinian People.
</P>
<P>
The conference will be opened by Colombian Foreign Minister
Guillermo Fernandez de Soto, and will be preceded by the
Preparatory Meeting at High Officials Level, to take place Friday.
</P>
<P>
The major topics of the conference will be international
security and disarmament, international law, economic cooperation,
sustainable development, human rights, women's promotion and
Colombia's peace process as well.
</P>
<P>
The conference will examine also issues dealing with the
creation of the International Criminal Court and the failure of
the trade negotiations Seattle round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
