<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Chief Warns Mission in Haiti Short of Funds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 5 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on Wednesday informed the United Nations General Assembly
that the resources for the International Civilian Support Mission
In Haiti (MICAH) are insufficient.
</P>
<P>
In a letter to the United Nations General Assembly, Annan said
no contributions have been received to date for the Trust Fund of
MICAH.
</P>
<P>
As a result, human rights and law and order activities, which
were to have been covered by voluntary contributions, cannot be
carried out, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Annan suggested that the Assembly consider closing the mission
and transferring its substantive activities to the U.N.
Development Program, rather than "preserving a presence in Haiti
which has only core staff and is unable to carry out the envisaged
activities in the areas of justice, human rights and police."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. chief also noted that the increasing tendency for the
United Nations to be "given mandates without the necessary
financial resources."
</P>
<P>
The mission began its mandate on March 16 with only core staff,
whose costs are covered through regular budgetary resources.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
