<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Kenya Takes Actions to Curb Road Accidents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Li Jinqi
</P>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Following Kenya's worst road
accident in which 76 people were killed last week, the Kenyan
government have taken swift actions to curb such road carnage and
save the peoples' lives.
</P>
<P>
Last Wednesday, two buses collided head-on on the
Nakuru-Kericho road in western Kenya, with one of the bus turned
into a fireball, as a result of overloading and overspeeding.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi last Thursday ordered the
police to set up road blocks for immediate crackdown on overloaded
buses and mutatus (mini-bus) to minimize road accidents and ensure
drivers are prosecuted to deter them from violating traffic laws
without punishment.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated that his government could not sit back and watch
Kenyans lose their lives because of reckless driving and lack of
action.
</P>
<P>
Moi also directed the Ministry of Roads and Public Works to
repair accident black spots and expand the sections of the highway
to give drivers a clear view of the road ahead.
</P>
<P>
In Kenya, recklessness, overloading and speeding by drivers of
public service vehicles are the major factors behind the rising
accident rates.
</P>
<P>
Local media reported that in the past two weeks alone, more
than 100 Kenyans have perished in road accidents.
</P>
<P>
It is a common scene in the capital Nairobi that the overpacked
matatus always overtake other vehicles regardless of traffic laws
and regulations.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan police across the country have swiftly responded to
Moi's instruction and placed road blocks on all major roads to
crack down on unroadworthy vehicles and those overloading and
speeding buses.
</P>
<P>
In Western Province where the bus collusion occurred, traffic
police on Monday alone impounded over 80 vehicles and arrested 25
drivers for overloading and speeding and other traffic offence.
</P>
<P>
While traffic police in Central Province have impounded 400
vehicles and arrested 243 drivers in the ongoing crackdown, which
began four days ago.
</P>
<P>
Justus Mwangi, traffic police officer in Western Province, said
the drivers netted in the crackdown operation would be charged
with overloading and speeding.
</P>
<P>
He warned that drivers or passengers who attempt to give
bribes to police officers will be apprehended on the spot, and
police officers who allow any overloaded vehicles to pass will
risk losing their jobs.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Police Commissioner Philemon Abong'o has ordered that
road signs be put up on the spot where two buses collided head-on
to caution drivers against overloading and speeding.
</P>
<P>
The police boss also urged local inspectors to conduct public
lectures on traffic code in schools and other institutions with a
view to enlightening the public in the respect.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the crackdown would continue until
discipline and sanity are restored on the roads.
</P>
<P>
According to a report by the International Federation of Red
Cross and Red Crescent Societies, Kenya is ranked among the top
six countries in the world with highest rate of road accidents.
</P>
<P>
The agency estimates that road accidents cost Kenya between 55
million to 70 million U.S. dollars annually although other
researchers put the loss at twice these figures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
