<HEADLINE> Mugabe Defends Farm Allocations to Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
Wednesday defended the issue of some senior officials in his
government acquiring farms, after British Foreign Minister of
State Peter Hain accused him of allocating land to "his cronies".
</P>
<P>
Mugabe told Zimbabwean reporters during a stop-over in Nairobi
on his return from the Africa-European Union summit in Cairo that
the number of ministers in his cabinet was so insignificant that
even if they all got farms under the land reform program this
would not make any impact on the program.
</P>
<P>
"Hain repeated that I was giving land to my 'cronies'. I said
my cabinet has only 23 ministers. Even if each one of them had
land they could not be in possession of the five million hectares
that the government intends to acquire for resettlement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Most of Zimbabwe's 12 million hectares of best farm land is
owned by 4, 000 whites.
</P>
<P>
Mines, Environment and Tourism Minister Simon Khaya Moyo and
Deputy Transport and Energy Minister Zenzo Nsimbi are among the
people that recently handed back their farms at the height of
adverse publicity pointing out that the properties were being
allocated to undeserving people.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers said they were withdrawing their applications
for those farms as they were closer to the communal lands.
</P>
<P>
The government recently came up with a policy decision that
farms close to communal lands should be used to resettle landless
people in those areas.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
