<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Civic Groups Concerned Over Rising Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's various civic groups on
Wednesday expressed concern over the upsurge in political violence
and urged political leaders to use their powers to curb
lawlessness.
</P>
<P>
The Legal Resources Foundation condemned the clash that erupted
last weekend in Harare between ex-combatants and demonstrators of
the National Constitutional Assembly.
</P>
<P>
It said: "The conduct of attackers, the slow reaction of the
riot police and their selective use of their powers of arrest are
examples of the breakdown of the rule of law in Zimbabwe."
</P>
<P>
The government and President Robert Mugabe should condemn the
violence, it added.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the National Business Forum said in a statement that
violence would tarnish the domestic and international image of the
country.
</P>
<P>
They said there was need to stop the "senseless violence" to
enable Zimbabwe to hold fair parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
"As business people, we find the prevalence of violence and
lawlessness having the potential to negate the efforts being made
by both the government and the business to create an environment
for national consensus building which will result in attracting
investment and lead to economic growth," they said.
</P>
<P>
The opposition Movement for Democratic Change also condemned
the violence that has been going on in the past weeks, but also
raised concern over lack of police intervention.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that more than 120 people have been arrested in
almost 40 cases of recent political violence, which has left two
people dead and 100 others injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
