<HEADLINE> Syrian Foreign Minister to Visit Egypt Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
said Wednesday that his Syrian counterpart Faruq Shareh will visit
Cairo early next week to discuss the latest developments in the
Mideast peace march, especially on the Syria track.
</P>
<P>
Shareh was to have paid the visit on Wednesday, but his trip was
delayed due to Egypt's busy schedule for the first Africa-Europe
summit attended by leaders of 67 African and European Union
countries, Moussa told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The postponement was reportedly decided during a phone call
Tuesday night between the two ministers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Egyptian Information Ministry said Shareh's trip
had been called off but gave no details.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak reportedly telephoned his
Syrian counterpart Hafez al-Assad on Tuesday, discussing
developments in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
After meeting United States President Bill Clinton in Washington
at the end of March, Mubarak said he planned to contribute to
efforts to unblock the Syrian-Israeli negotiations and that he
could soon meet Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
The statement followed the failure of the March 26 U.S.-Syrian
summit in Geneva aimed at revitalizing the Syrian-Israeli talks,
which have been stalled since January due to disputes over Israeli
full withdrawal from the Golan Heights that Israel seized from
Syria in the 1967 Mideast War.
</P>
<P>
Chances of resuming the negotiations were hit by the failure of
the Geneva summit. Israel has confirmed its intention to pull its
troops out of south Lebanon, even without an agreement with Lebanon
or Syria. Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, has some 35,000
troops in Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
