<HEADLINE> Annan's Envoy Holds talks with Lebanese President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 5 (Xinhua) - United Nations Secretary General Kofi
Annan's envoy Rord Larsen Wednesday held talks with Lebanese
President Emile Lahoud over the future of south Lebanon against the
backdrop of upcoming Israeli withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Larson, who arrived here in the afternoon for a two-day visit,
has a plan to meet with Lebanese leaders and brief them of the
results of the talks between Kofi Annan and Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
Larsen delivered Annan's news statement to Lahoud, which was
released in Geneva Tuesday after his meeting with Levy and
mentioned Israel's resolve to fulfill a withdrawal from south
Lebanon and cooperate with United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Larsen said Annan is waiting for a formal reply from Lebanon
concerning Israel's offer.
</P>
<P>
Lahoud issued a memorandum after his talks with Larsen,
condemning Israel's ferocity over Lebanon since 1978 and voicing
doubt about the Jewish country's real intention of the pullout.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that Palestinian guerrillas will continue
attacks on Israel after its unilateral withdrawal, indicating that
the Lebanese government can not entirely control Palestinian
guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
There are some 370, 000 Palestinian refugees living in Lebanon
since the founding of Israel and the first Middle East war in 1948.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has repeatedly reiterated that Palestinian refugees
should return home while Israel has rejected the request. 
</P>
