<HEADLINE> Finding Confirms Severe Loss of Ozone In Arctic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Ozone have lost more than 60
percent in the Arctic stratosphere near 18-kilometer altitude
during one of the coldest stratospheric winters on record, the
European Commission confirmed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This is one of the most substantial ozone losses at this
altitude in the Arctic, the European Union (EU)'s executive arm
said in a statement when releasing a research finding conducted by
European and American scientists.
</P>
<P>
"Measurements from the largest international campaign ever
investigating stratospheric ozone depletion have provided more
insight into the processes that control stratospheric ozone,"the
Commission said.
</P>
<P>
"They have also reinforced concerns that the Arctic ozone may
continue to decline despite the benefits of reductions in
stratospheric chlorine levels due to the global climate change."
</P>
<P>
EU research commissioner Philippe Busquin said EU researchers
and an American team demonstrate "how important it is for Europe
to create a European Research Area where the best European
scientists collaborate in a network".
</P>
<P>
"This project will provide decision makers with a sound base to
judge the effects of ozone depletion on the environment and on
citizen's health," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
