<HEADLINE> U.N. Ponders Measures Against Sanction Violators </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Security Council is
considering taking punitive measures against the countries proved
to have violated the sanctions on the rebel National Union for the
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
Local informed sources on Wednesday quoted Chairman of the U.N.
 Sanctions Committee on Angola and Canadian Ambassador to the U.N.
Robert Fowler as saying that the possibility to impose sanctions
on the violating countries is contained in a draft resolution
submitted by Canada to the Security Council, adding that this is
however a "very complex" issue.
</P>
<P>
Canada proposed that the Security Council examine the issue
after a six- month study on whether the countries that allegedly
violated the sanctions have taken the necessary measures to avoid
repetition, he said.
</P>
<P>
The special report released last month by the U.N. sanctions
committee accused Togo, Burkina Faso, Rwanda, among others, of
breaching the U.N. sanctions meant to cut off military supplies to
the rebels led by Jonas Savimbi. 
</P>
