<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Arabia Completes Privatization of Power Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia on Wednesday
announced the completion of the full privatization of its power
sector by establishing the Saudi Electricity Company (SEC), a 9
billion-U.S. dollar group in which the government owns 50 percent
of the shares.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Commerce Minister Osama Faqih said the SEC was formed by a
merger of 10 regional electrical companies, the Saudi Press Agency
monitored here reported.
</P>
<P>
Faqih said the Riyadh-based SEC will generate, transform and
distribute electricity in Saudi Arabia, as well as selling and
purchasing energy service.
</P>
<P>
It will also take part and invest in domestic and foreign energy
ventures, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi government decided to privatize the electricity sector
and establish the new company last November, hoping it would "
provide best services to its clients according to the accredited
technical standards and with the least cost."
</P>
<P>
The electricity sector is the second public sector to be
privatized by Riyadh, after it privatized the communications sector
in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
Since early 1996, when Saudi King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz entrusted,
after suffering a stroke, his half-brother Crown Prince Abdullah
Ibn Abdul-Aziz to take charge of the country's daily affairs, the
Gulf kingdom has been striving to diversify its oil economy and
encourage a greater role of the private sector.
</P>
<P>
The private sector grew by a moderate 2.4 percent last year,
slightly higher than the 2.12-percent growth in 1998. Its
contribution to the Saudi gross domestic product (GDP) was
estimated at 38 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
