<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 55 Tons of Narcotics Seized in Iran's Khorasan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Over 55 tons of narcotics were
seized in Iran's northeastern province of Khorasan during the past
Iranian calendar year which ended March 19, Commander of the
Provincial Security Forces Bahram Norouzi said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The consignment, which was seized during 272-day operations,
represented an increase of 8.7 percent from the previous year,
Norouzi told the Islamic Republic News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Five tons of the haul was heroin while the rest was opium, he
said, adding that 285 traffickers were killed in armed clashes, 515
injured while 33 Iranian anti-drug personnel lost their lives.
</P>
<P>
During the year, 8,747 smugglers, 423 distributors and dealers
and 21,119 addicts were also arrested in the province which border
Afghanistan, the world's largest drug producing center, he added.
</P>
<P>
Iranian Vice President for Executive Affairs Mohammad Hashemi
said on Monday that Iran confiscated over 253 tons of different
kinds of narcotics in 1999, including six tons of heroin, 22 tons
of morphine, 204 tons of opium, 18 tons of hashish and three tons
of others.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to foreign envoys based in Tehran, he called for
international cooperation among world countries to help Iran in its
campaigns against drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Iran is a main transit route for drugs smuggled from
Afghanistan, the world's largest opium producer, and neighboring
Pakistan to Europe and oil-rich Gulf Arab states.
</P>
<P>
Iran started harsh anti-drug campaigns in 1989 after the Iranian
Majlis or parliament passed an anti-drug law authorizing capital
punishment for drug traffickers.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that some 2900 anti-drug forces have been killed in
operations since the Islamic revolution in 1979. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
