<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Fines Truck Drivers for Stowaways </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen illegal immigrants were
found in trucks and the drivers fined 32,000 pounds (51,000 U.S.
dollars) in the first three days of a British crackdown on
stowaways, the Home Office said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"As per my latest information, there have been four trucks
found with 16 clandestine entrants aboard," a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The Home Office declined to give the nationalities of the
immigrants, who were detained, or of the drivers.
</P>
<P>
They were the first drivers to be punished under the
Immigration and Asylum Act passed last year, which imposed a 2,000
pound (3,200 dollar) penalty for each person arriving without the
correct papers.
</P>
<P>
The fines were introduced by the government in an attempt to
force lorry drivers to tighten up security and search their
vehicles before boarding cross-Channel ferris.
</P>
<P>
The crackdown on asylum seekers follows a vitriolic press
campaign and opposition charges that the Labor government has been
soft on immigration.
</P>
<P>
Other measures include plans to scatter immigrants across the
country and pay refugees a living allowance in shopping vouchers
rather than in cash.
</P>
<P>
Britain received 71,160 asylum applications in 1999, the second
highest tally in the European Union after Germany which had 95,115.
</P>
<P>
The largest group coming to Britain were 11,465 applicants from
the former Yugoslavia. Asylum seekers from Somalia and Sri Lanka
were the next most numerous -- 7,495 and 5,130 respectively in
1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
