<HEADLINE> Pakistan Urges UN to Persuade India to Resume Dialogue On Kashmir Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan on Wednesday urged
the United Nations and the international community to persuade
India to resume dialogue over Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
The move came after Shamshad Ahmad, Pakistan's Ambassador to
the United Nations, met with the president of the Security Council
for the current month this morning. Ahmad briefed the president
about the volatile situation in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Ambassador Ahmad said "Pakistan is seriously
concerned about the escalating tension."
</P>
<P>
"On our part, we have always sought tension-free and good
neighborly relations with India on the basis of a final settlement
of the Jammu and Kashmir dispute. We have always shown restraint
and will continue to do so. but we will defend ourselves against
any act of aggression," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I informed the president about our recent formal offer to
India for resumption of dialogue at any time, any place and at any
level without any precondition. This is rooted in our belief that
all disputes should be resolved through peaceful means," he said.
</P>
<P>
"As always in the past, India's response regrettably has again
been negative," he said.
</P>
<P>
"I told the president that Pakistan seeks a fair, just and
equitable settlement of the Kashmir dispute in accordance with the
wishes of the people Jammu and Kashmir," the Ambassador added.
</P>
</TEXT>
