<HEADLINE> JMC Meeting Prolonged Due to Language Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The sixth plenary session of the
Joint Military Commission under the Lusaka Ceasefire Agreement,
which is expected to last for two days, is set to be prolonged
into Thursday due to language problem.
</P>
<P>
"There is too much translation and too much documentation to
study and discuss. Now we are having three languages being used at
the meeting," Acting Chairman of JMC Timothy Kazembe, a Zambian
brigadier general, told reporters at the International Conference
Center here Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is aimed at preparing documents for the meeting of
the Joint Political Committee due to convene Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Eighteen members of the JMC from nine parties discussed issues
concerning cementing borders among the various parties in the
Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC). The first JMC meeting
ended with identification of their borders. However, their
borders changed a lot due to reported violations during the time.
</P>
<P>
Members of the JMC said that they did not have differences
whatsoever and expected resolutions to be reached Thursday when
they would issue a statement.
</P>
<P>
The JMC, established under the Lusaka agreement inked by all
parties to the 19-month-long conflict in the DRC, is a mechanism
designed for the monitoring of cease-fire among the belligerent
groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
