<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.African President to Attend Summit of Group of 77 in Cuba </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 5 (Xinhua) -- South African President Thabo
Mbeki, also Chairman of the Non-Aligned Movement, is expected to
attend the four- day summit of Group of 77 in Havana, Cuba, next
week, South African Foreign Affairs Department announced on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The department's spokesman Ronnie Mamoepa said Foreign Affairs
Minister Nkosazana Dlamini-Zuma will lead a ministerial delegation
to Havana, which will also include Trade and Industry Minister
Alec Erwin and Arts, Culture, Science and Technology Minister Ben
Ngubane.
</P>
<P>
Globalization, South-South co-operation, North-South
co-operation and knowledge and technology will be the top issues
discussed at the gathering.
</P>
<P>
Mamoepa said there is a general view within the Group of 77
that the interests of the South has been somewhat neglected in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
"There is concern that the United Nations does not focuses
sufficiently on development issues, that the South has little say
in the governance of the global economy and that the benefits
flowing from globalization and multilateral trade agreements have
accrued disproportionately to the North," he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Mamoepa said South Africa hopes that the summit will contribute
to advancing the debate on people-centered development, increasing
momentum for the democratization of the UN and the reform of the
global economic order.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, South Africa is also expected to repeat during the
meeting its call for an early resumption of trade negotiations
within the framework of the World Trade Organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
