<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, March 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM -- One out of ten Tanzanians volunteering to
donate blood at the largest hospital in Dar es Salaam were found
to be HIV positive, the African newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a medical study conducted by the Muhimbili University
College of Health Sciences, it was revealed that 522 out of the 6,
000 people who lined up for blood donation at the Muhimbili
Medical Center last year were tested positive for HIV.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, HIV was the most prevalent cause for
blood infection, accounting for 8.7 percent of blood donation
cases at the center. (Tanzania-AIDS)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
PYONGYANG -- The Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK)
and Japan started their ninth round of talks here Wednesday over
normalizing of diplomatic ties between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
A Japanese official, who asked not to be named, told reporters
after the morning session that the DPRK delegation "called for
settling of the historical account, and sought apology and
compensation" from Japan.
</P>
<P>
Jong Thae Hwa, who heads the DPRK's delegation, was quoted as
saying, "All our people are closely watching the talks, and we
want to lead the talks to success in line with their hopes."
</P>
<P>
Kojiro Takano, who leads the Japanese side, repeated Japan's
apology, but again rejected any compensation during the session
this morning. (DPRK-Japan-Talks)
</P>
