- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Namdar Zanganeh announced
on Wednesday that the largest sweet gas field in the world has
been discovered in southern Iran.
</P>
<P>
Zanganeh said that the independent onshore gas field has an
estimated reserve of more than 445 billion cubic meters of gas and
over 240 million barrels of liquid gas, the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Tabnak gas field with an value of about 16.5
billion U.S. dollars was discovered in the southern Fars province
by the National Iranian Oil Exploration Company (NIOEC).
</P>
<P>
The exploration work started in 1998 and so far the drilling
has reached 2,245 meters deep with a cost of 30 billion rials (
about 10 million dollars at the official rate), he said. (Iran-Gas-
Discovery)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- A European airplane that landed in Baghdad without
getting prior U.N. permission departed on Wednesday morning for
Rome, Italy, after completing its mission in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The plane took off at 10:25 (0725 GMT) from the Al-Rashed
military airport in the southern suburbs of Baghdad, reported the
Iraqi News Agency (INA).
</P>
<P>
The plane, carrying three people from France and Italy, landed
at the Al-Rashed airport on Monday evening defying the decade-long
U.N. embargo on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It was the first group that arrived in Baghdad by plane
disregarding the U.N. resolutions that require all flights to or
from Iraq must get approval from the U.N. Sanctions Committee. (
Iraq-Europe-Plane)
</P>
