<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Northern Border Residents Clash With Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Dozens of residents in northern
Israel clashed with police on Wednesday in a demonstration against
what they say is a lack of security in advance of Israel's planned
withdrawal from the occupied buffer zone in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The residents of the Margaliot village, which is located just a
few meters from the border, burned tires and blocked a road in the
village during the protest. They clashed at one point with the
police and fire-fighters attempting to douse the burning tires.
</P>
<P>
"They are turning us into Israel's front line," the village
secretary Eitan David told the Israel Radio, adding that "we don't
want to be soldiers, but want to be citizens like everyone else and
allow our children to go and play like in Tel Aviv and Jerusalem,
without fear."
</P>
<P>
The residents of the areas have asked the government to improve
their security facilities in light of the planned Israel's troop
withdrawal from the so-called security zone, which Israel set up in
1985 with a self-proclaimed purpose of protecting its northern
border areas from cross-border guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak decided to pullout the Israeli troops
from the zone by July this year with or without a peace agreement
with Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
On the security problem along the border, Deputy Defense
Minister Ephraim Sneh said Wednesday that it is impossible for the
government to provide each resident in the north with a security
room.
</P>
<P>
But it is possible to provide a security room for three or four
people or each family and the government has this plan in mind,
Sneh said.
</P>
<P>
In the event of rocket attacks launched by Lebanese guerrillas
in south lebanon, local residents in the north usually enter the
security rooms for self-protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli FM Praises Annan's Efforts on Lebanon Withdrawal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy Wednesday thanked United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan
for his efforts to ensure a quiet and safe withdrawal of Israeli
troops from south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Israel Radio, Levy said Israel agrees with
Annan to his ongoing consultations with all sides concerned over
the withdrawal issue.
</P>
<P>
Levy was referring to Annan's dispatch of a special envoy to
Beirut earlier in the day. The envoy is to brief Lebanese leaders
on the meeting between Annan and Levy at the U.N. office in Geneva
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Annan told Levy that he plans to help Israel
carry out the withdrawal on the basis of U.N. Security Council
Resolution 425, according to a statement issued by Levy's office.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, which was passed in 1978 after Israel launched a
large-scale aggression against Lebanon in the name of wiping out
Palestinian guerrillas there, calls for an immediate and
unconditional Israeli pullout from all Lebanese territory and for a
return of full sovereignty to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Israel is planning to pull out its troops under the resolution
from the so-called security zone in south Lebanon to the
international border between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The 15-kilometer-deep buffer zone was set up by Israel in 1985
with a self-claimed aim of preventing cross-border guerrilla
attacks on its north. But mounting Israeli casualties in the zone
have spurred a growing public pressure for a pullout.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet on March 5 gave backing to a key pledge made
by Prime Minister Ehud Barak to withdraw from the zone by July,
with or without a peace deal with Syria, the major power broker in
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian talks, which resumed last December after a
45-month break, broke off again in January over a dispute on the
fate of the Golan Heights, a strategic Syrian plateau seized by
Israel in the 1967 Middle East war. 
</P>
<P>
The latest effort to revive the talks, a summit meeting between
Syrian President Hafez al-Assad and United States President Bill
Clinton in Geneva on March 26, failed to produce any progress as
expected.
</P>
<P>
Some strategy experts predicted that in such a case, Hezbollah,
the Shiite Muslim militia fighting to end Israeli occupation since
1980s, will escalate its activities against Israeli soldiers and
even launch attacks on Israel's northern settlements.
</P>
<P>
To prevent such ugly things to happen, Barak's administration
had resorted to the mandate of the United Nations and Resolution
425 to ensure international support and assistance for its pullout,
although Israel never openly accepted the resolution before.
</P>
<P>
Barak and Levy reportedly hope the endorsement of Annan and
international certification of Israel's efforts will prevent future
attacks by Hezbollah, or other militant groups which will occupy
the vacuum areas after Israel Defense Forces leaves there this
July.
</P>
<P>
Israeli leaders are of the view that the international support
will at least make Israel's future retaliation operations against
such attacks win more legitimacy and sympathy.
</P>
<P>
In the past few weeks, Israel officials were also promoting the
idea of extending authority of the current U.N. Interim Force in
Lebanon (UNIFIL) to the whole security zone to ensure there will be
no vacuum left.
</P>
<P>
The 4,500-strong peacekeeping troops from nine countries are
currently deployed primarily in the western and central sectors of
south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Annan promised Tuesday that if it is necessary to increase the
number of or strengthen the mandate of the UNIFIL, he will consider
proposing a new resolution beyond 425. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
