<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Court Blocks Controversial Release of Jewish Murderer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli High Court of Justice
Wednesday officially put off the controversial release of Yoram
Shkolnik, a Jewish life prisoner sentenced for murdering a
Palestinian, for at least several weeks.
</P>
<P>
The ruling was issued by a seven-member panel of the High Court
after they heard the appealing filed by liberal Knesset
(parliament) member Zahava Galn against the planned release of
Shkolnik, which is originally due to happen on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The judges decreed in the ruling that the release should be
delayed until the court issued its final ruling of the case, which
usually could take several weeks, Israel Wire reported.
</P>
<P>
The crime took place in March 1993, when a Palestinian man named
Abu Sabah was picked up hitchhiking by two Jewish settlers. The
settles later claimed he attacked them with a knife and they
subdued him and tied his hands and feet.
</P>
<P>
After hearing about the news from a two-way radio in his car,
Skolnik drove to the area, pulled out his Uzi submachine gun and
shot dead the Arab man, who was lying face down on the ground at
that time. 
</P>
<P>
Skolnik was later convicted of murder and sentenced to life
imprisonment for the killing. His sentence was commuted to 15 years
by President Ezer Weizman in 1997, and then reduced again to 11
years in 1999.
</P>
<P>
A Prison Parole Board decided last month to grant an early
release to him because of "his contrition and his good behavior in
prison." 
</P>
<P>
The controversial release immediately prompted objections from
the State Attorney's Office and the Arab parties, who satirized
that the life of an Arab is worth very little, especially if the
one who takes it is a Jew.
</P>
<P>
The Arab parties even submitted a no-confidence motion over the
release. Legislator Galon, from the left-wing Meretz party, also
called upon the High Court to stop the planned release, insisting
it is crazy for a convicted murderer to only serve seven years in
jail.
</P>
<P>
Galon's stand got support from Attorney General Elyakim
Rubinstein and State Attorney Edna Arbel, who argued that such a
decision should be annulled on the grounds of its extreme
irregularity.
</P>
<P>
Justice Aaron Barak, the president of the High Court of Justice,
appointed the seven-judge panel to hear the appeal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Takes Steps to Ensure Security Along LoC: Musharraf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's Chief Executive
General Pervez Musharraf Wednesday said that "adequate measures"
are being taken to ensure security along the Line of Control (LoC)
in Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
He said this while presiding over a meeting of the federal
cabinet, according to an official press release issued here.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the recent "media hype being generated by India"
about increasing tension in the region, Musharraf said that the
security environment in the region is being constantly reviewed
and monitored.
</P>
<P>
The LoC divides vigilant Pakistani and Indian troops in the
disputed area of Kashmir, where they fought two of their three
wars during the past 53 years and the Kargil conflict brought them
to the very brink of a third all-out Kashmir war last summer.
</P>
<P>
The tension in the LoC area has been high this year when
several military clashes occurred and, especially, after 35 Sikhs
were murdered in India-controlled Kashmir late March, in which
India accused Pakistan of involvement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
