<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Revenue Collections Suffer Marginal Shortfall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On an aggregated basis, India's total direct and indirect tax
collections for the past financial year was 1.65136 trillion
rupees (38.4 billion U.S. dollars) against the targeted figure of
1.6613 trillion rupees (38.63 billion dollars), leaving a deficit
of 9.94 billion rupees (231.2 million dollars), the Press Trust of
India quoted Kumar as saying in the northeastern city of Calcutta.
</P>
<P>
The shortfall of revenue collections was due to a deficit in
income tax, a category of direct taxes. Targeted at 266.84 billion
rupees (6.21 billion dollars), the actual collection of income tax
was only 243.25 billion rupees (5.66 billion dollars), said Kumar.
</P>
<P>
Collections of other categories of taxes, such as customs,
central excise, corporate tax and interest taxes, were all
slightly higher than the estimated figures, he added.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, he said, last year's revenue collections had
grown by nearly 20 percent compared with the figure of the 1998-99
financial year, which was merely 1.37967 trillion rupees (32.09
billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
The Indian government has set the target for revenue
collections in the 2000-01 financial year, starting this month and
concluding at the end of next March, at 2.04 trillion rupees (47.
44 billion dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
