<HEADLINE> Judgment in Sharif Hijacking Case to Be Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's deposed Prime
Minister Nawaz Sharif will hear final judgment on Thursday of the
Anti-Terrorist Court No. One (ATC-1) in southern Pakistani city of
Karachi in the plane hijacking case.
</P>
<P>
Under Pakistan's Anti-Terrorism Act 1997, the maximum
punishment for hijacking is death sentence.
</P>
<P>
Nawaz Sharif and other six co-accused including his brother
Shahbaz Sharif will be present in the court.
</P>
<P>
In the case, which was first lodged by an army officer on
November 10, 1999, the former prime minister is accused of
hijacking a civil flight on October 12, 1999, attempted murder and
criminal conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 passengers, including General Pervez Musharraf, now
the chief executive of Pakistan, were on board the allegedly
hijacked aircraft.
</P>
<P>
The ATC-1 began the regular hearing of the trial on January 26,
2000 when accused-turned-approver former Director General
Aminullah Chaudhry recorded his statement in the court as the
first prosecution witness. 
</P>
