<HEADLINE> Indian, U.S. Intelligence Agencies To Cooperate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Decisions to this effect were made here during a meeting
Wednesday between U.S. Federal Bureau of Investigation (FBI)
Director Louis Freeh and Indian Special Secretary in charge of
internal security M. B. Kaushal.
</P>
<P>
Freeh, who arrived in New Delhi on Tuesday for a three-day
official visit, also agreed to train Indian police officials in
specialized crime like cyber crime, computer crime and modern
investigation techniques, the release said.
</P>
<P>
Enforcement agencies of the two countries will share
information on arm trafficking and smuggling, according to the
release.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources here said that FBI is likely to open an office
in the Indian capital and foster closer contacts with New Delhi
for joint cooperation in tacking international terrorism and other
crimes.
</P>
<P>
India and the U.S. set up a joint working group on counter-
terrorism under a decision made by Indian External Affairs
Minister Jaswant Singh and U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott when they met in London last January.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the two countries had agreed to begin negotiations on
a mutual legal assistance treaty aimed at establishing an
investigation and prosecution of crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
