<HEADLINE> Bush, Gore Win Presidential Primaries in Pennsylvania, Wisconsin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Vice President Al Gore and
Texas Governor George W. Bush won presidential primaries in
Pennsylvania and Wisconsin Tuesday, gaining more than enough
delegate support for presidential nominations.
</P>
<P>
In Pennsylvania, with 99 percent of precincts reporting, Bush
won the Republican primary with 73 percent, or 470,637 votes,
according to unofficial returns. The remaining votes were shared
by his former rivals.
</P>
<P>
On the Democratic side, with 99 percent of precincts reporting,
Gore won with 74 percent, or 517,901 votes.
</P>
<P>
In Wisconsin's Republican primary, with 96 percent of precincts
reporting, Bush won 69 percent of the vote, or 324,796 votes.
</P>
<P>
In the Democratic contest, with 96 percent of precincts
reporting, Gore won 89 percent of the vote, or 313,357 votes.
</P>
<P>
Pennsylvania, with 23 Electoral College votes, could be a
critical swing state in the presidential election in November.
Wisconsin has 11 electoral votes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
