<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three African Organizations to Cooperate in Transport Systems </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Three African organizations have
signed an agreement over the development of efficient, safe and
integrated transport systems in eastern and southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
These organizations are the Common Market for Eastern and
Southern Africa (COMESA), the Southern Africa Transport and
Communications Commission (SATCC) and the United Nations Economic
Commission for Africa Sub-Regional Development Center for Southern
Africa (ECA/SRDC-SA).
</P>
<P>
A press release obtained from COMESA Center in Lusaka on
Wednesday said the three organizations had agreed to jointly
promote private sector participation in transport infrastructure
development and services.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to work for improvement of road safety on
international routes, harmonization of definitions and selection
of performance indicators in selected transit corridors and
promotion of measures to prevent and control the spread of
HIV/AIDS in transit transport corridors.
</P>
<P>
Opportunity will be provided for the regional organizations to
present case studies on ongoing activities in eastern and southern
Africa, the release said.
</P>
<P>
It said that a proposal for the improvement of the road safety
in the region will be prepared and submitted to Africa Development
Bank for financing.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of HIV/AIDS along the transit transport corridors,
it was agreed that the intervention of the regional economic
groupings through their transport programs would greatly augment
national and global programs in the prevention and control of the
pandemic.
</P>
<P>
The organizations will therefore cooperate in building up
information and educational elements to go together with programs
such as road safety and transit traffic facilitation, the release
said.
</P>
<P>
The organizations will also cooperate in facilitating the
successful implementation of transit road user charges.
</P>
<P>
According to the release, COMESA and the Southern African
Development Community (SADC) will prepare a manual on
implementation of the harmonized user charges to be used by the
road transport operations/agents and the regulators who manage the
road networks.
</P>
<P>
It is COMESA's policy to consult and collaborate with the other
regional economic groupings in order to eliminate duplication in
the use of resources and enhance complementarities which exist
amply in the region, the release said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Tourism Suffers 50 Percent Business Reduction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's tourism industry has
suffered a 50-percent decline in tourist arrivals due to the fuel
crisis and the prevailing political uncertainty, the Zimbabwe
Tourism Authority (ZTA) said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
ZTA Chief Executive Etherton Mpisaunga told the Zimbabwe News
Agency that the industry estimates that between 40 and 50 percent
of business has been lost since the fuel crisis began last
November, compounded by the pre-election political bickering and
violence.
</P>
<P>
"The picture being painted in the foreign print and electronic
media is one of a not stable situation," he said, adding that the
prevailing situation nullified ZTA's efforts to clean up the
country's image abroad.
</P>
<P>
Chief executive Herbert Nkala of Rainbow Tourism Group, the
country's main tourism company, told the core group of the
National Economic Consultative Forum recently that tourist
arrivals within the group were about 40 percent less than that of
last year.
</P>
<P>
He said there was a general lack of confidence in what is
happening in the country as the fuel crisis entered its sixth
month.
</P>
<P>
"These issues are fundamental and should be urgently resolved.
Tourist arrivals are now 30 to 40 percent less than those of last
year and we still cannot tell those inquiring when the fuel
problem will be solved," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tourism is the third largest contributor to Zimbabwe's Gross
Domestic Growth after agriculture and manufacturing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
