<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Releases a Long-held Lebanese Detainee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Israel freed Rassan Dirani, a 35-
year-old Lebanese citizen who was abducted 14 years ago, from
administrative detention on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Tel Aviv District Court issued the order of release 10 days ago,
but the gag order preventing media from publishing the news was
only lifted Wednesday, according to Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Dirani, who was detained by pro-Israeli Lebanese Christian
militias and then transferred to an Israeli jail, will be handed
over to the International Red Cross and return to Lebanon
immediately after his release.
</P>
<P>
His lawyer revealed that his client is mental ill now because of
the long-time detention, arguing that Dirani's only so-called crime
was that he is a nephew of Mustafa Dirani, security chief of the
Lebanese resistance militia Amal.
</P>
<P>
Mustafa Dirani, who was also captured by Israeli agents in a
special operation in 1994, is still held in administrative
detention and no charges have been filed against him.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that 21 Lebanese had been held in Israeli
administrative detention and they are used by Israel as bargaining
chips for information or return of Ron Arad, a Israeli Air Force
navigator who has been missing since 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Five of them were freed in last December and two more were freed
in January this year.
</P>
<P>
Arad parachuted from his hit Phantom fighter on Lebanese soils
in October 1986 and then was reportedly captured by Mustafa Dirani,
who is believed to have "sold" Arad later to either Lebanese
Hezbollah guerrillas or Iranian elements.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in March, Mustafa Dirani alleged that he was tortured
and raped when he was under interrogation. He sued the state for 6
million shekels (about 1.5 million U.S. dollars) in compensation in
a lawsuit filed in Tel Aviv District Court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0072 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flower Clock From China Settles in Phnom Penh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A big flower clock from China
was settled Wednesday in Wat Phnom at the center of Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
A hand-over ceremony was held at Wat Phnom with the
participation of Governor of Phnom Penh Municipality Chea Sophara
and Counselor of Chinese Embassy to Cambodia Zhang Jinfeng and
others.
</P>
<P>
The clock, worth of more than 90,000 U.S. dollars, was
presented by China Yunnan Corporation for International Techno-
Economic Cooperation to the Phnom Penh Municipality.
</P>
<P>
Chea Sophara expressed his thanks to the Chinese company,
saying the beautiful flower clock not only beautified the
environment of Phnom Penh city, but also marks the friendship
between the people of our two countries. "It will certainly
strengthen the friendship and cooperation between our two peoples,
" Chea Sophara said.
</P>
<P>
The flower clock, replacing the old one from France, has a
diameter of about 20 meters and controlled by computer. In
addition to an automatic GPS timing system, the clock has an
automatic fault diagnosis system and a maximum power for working
36 hours even if the alternating current was interrupted.
</P>
<P>
With the big ben sound, the clock can also automatically
broadcast Cambodia's national anthem twice a day at the time when
the sun is rising and sinking.
</P>
<P>
Wat Phnom temple is a symbol of Phnom Penh, which was built in
1434 to house sacred relics. Even today it remains the highest
artificial hill in Phnom Penh and center of many forms of leisure
activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
