<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Estrada to Ignore Charges of Protest Movements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
said Wednesday he will no longer devote time answering the charges
hurled against him by what he called power-hungry protest groups.
</P>
<P>
The president said in a statement that the groups are make a
lot of noise now because of the upcoming elections in 2001.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that he is more committed than ever to making sure
that his presidency will help the poor cross over to a more decent
quality of life.
</P>
<P>
"I have a sworn duty to serve our people and not just the
elitists.I will continue working to solve our nation's problems,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The president questioned the credibility of some of those
behind the protest movements. Some of them, he said, lost to him
in the last elections, and some of them are facing charges of
graft.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Presidential Palace asked Department of Social
Welfare and Development Secretary Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo to
resign from her post due to her alleged links to moves to oust
President Estrada.
</P>
<P>
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said Wednesday he made the
challenge due to Arroyo's silence over moves by the opposition
party to oust the president.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said Arroyo, who is also the country's vice president,
will be asked to explain her involvement in the oust Estrada
campaign by the opposition when she come back from her foreign
visit.
</P>
<P>
Zamora's challenge came after Senate Minority Floor Leader
Teofisto Guingona wrote Estrada an open letter on Monday, asking
him to resign from his post.
</P>
<P>
Guingona and Arroyo belong to the same political party, Laka-
NUCD.
</P>
</TEXT>
