<HEADLINE> Lack of Sponsorship Might Cost China Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Time is running out for the
organizers of the China Rally race to find adequate money before
the International Automobile Federation (FIA) meets in Paris on
April 6, which will decide the fate of the race.
</P>
<P>
After a successful year of 1999 when China staged the first
ever World Championship Rally event in Huairou County in Beijing
suburbs, an official of the China Automobile Association (CAA)
said they had failed to find suitable sponsors before the deadline.
</P>
<P>
"We're waiting for the final decision from the FIA meeting,"
the CAA official said here on Wednesday. The official declined to
be named.
</P>
<P>
With the principal sponsors pulling out of the race last month,
the organizers have been looking for big-name companies worldwide
to fund the event.
</P>
<P>
The race was originally scheduled for September 7-10, but teams
need at least half a year to make their preparations.
</P>
<P>
But the official said the race would still be included in the
Asian-Pacific Rally circuit.
</P>
<P>
Frenchman Didier Auriol, driving a Toyota, won the China Rally
last year. 
</P>
