<HEADLINE> Football to Highlight Peace Year in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Football, which is not so popular
in the Philippines, will highlight this year's national
celebrations of the UN-designated International Year for the
Culture of Peace and Thanksgiving and the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of various government agencies and non-
governmental organizations (NGOs) signed Wednesday a memorandum of
co-operation to ensure the success of the First Philippine
Football Championship Cup, also dubbed as Football for Peace.
</P>
<P>
The football tournament is one of the projects lined up by the
Philippine Retirement Authority Members Association Foundation,
Coalition of NGOs, and the United Nations Information Center for
the Philippines, as organizers.
</P>
<P>
"Our aim is to construct the defense of peace in the minds of
men because we are one in the belief that peace must be founded in
the intellectual and moral solidarity of mankind," said the
memorandum.
</P>
<P>
The plan will bring football from the barangays (villages) in
all the country's 16 regions and "provide a venue or honest
competition and teamwork."
</P>
<P>
Under the rules of the tournament, all the regions shall be
eligible to compete, with each region to be represented by not
more than one team per category in the final round.
</P>
<P>
Age levels are Class A (Men), 19-21 years old; Class B, (Boys)
15-18 years old; Class C (Girls), 15-18 years old; and Class D (
Boys), 12-14 years old.
</P>
<P>
The tournament shall be divided into two parts -- the group
tournament and the final round (champions elimination). 
</P>
</TEXT>
