<HEADLINE> 3 HK Teenage Computer Hackers Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 5 (Xinhua) - Three Hong Kong teenagers were
sentenced after they were convicted of computer hacking offenses
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Eastern Magistracy sentenced two teenagers to
detention center and another to six months' jail.
</P>
<P>
The trio were arrested by officers from the Computer Crime
Section, Commercial Crime Bureau of Police during investigations
into the activities of a computer hacking syndicate last May.
</P>
<P>
A police spokesman welcomed the ruling, noting that custodial
sentence would have deterrent effect to a certain extent upon
computer hacking.
</P>
<P>
On March 21, the three teenagers pleaded guilty to 49 charges
including access to computer with a dishonest gain, criminal
damage in respect of compromising account particulars, dealing
with property known or reasonably believed to represent proceeds
of an indictable offense under the Organized and Serious Crimes
Ordinance and making infringing copies of copyrighted works.
</P>
<P>
Two of the defendants, both aged 19, were convicted of hacking
into other people's computers to obtain account details and
passwords, and sold them for profits.
</P>
<P>
One of them was sentenced to six months in jail while the other
is to serve custodial sentence in detention center.
</P>
<P>
The third defendant, aged 18, was also sentenced to detention
center after he was convicted of having sold compact discs
containing songs downloaded from the Internet or dubbed from
copyrighted computer discs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
