<P>
RIYADH -- The board of executive directors of the Islamic Bank
for Development has approved new funds exceeding 225 million U.S.
dollars for member states and the Islamic communities in non-member
states.
</P>
<P>
The funds include 100 million dollars to finance 11 development
projects in nine member states, about 2 million dollars allocated
for non-member states.
</P>
<P>
BETHLEHEM -- The Palestinian National Authority (PNA) has signed
an agreement with the European Union (EU) which will enable the
Palestinians to import and export goods through the Gaza
international airport.
</P>
<P>
PNA Minister of Planning and International Cooperation Nabil
Sha'ath said under the deal, the EU will help the Palestinians
build freighting facilities in the Gaza airport. And efforts are
underway to speed up construction works for the freighting
operations to start at the beginning of next year.
</P>
<P>
JEDDAH -- The Saudi government on Monday has approved to grant
visas to foreigners wishing to visit the kingdom as tourists, but
not for the purposes of work or pilgrimage.
</P>
<P>
The new visas will enable foreigners to visit historical sites
and attend exhibitions and conferences in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
The number of tourists arriving in Saudi Arabia during the next
five years is expected to reach 3 million and their total spending
will amount to about 10 billion rials (2.7 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- Turkey has started working on a 300-million-U.S.-
dollar project to bring water to the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
northern part of Cyprus through an underwater pipeline, reported
Turkish Daily News on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
State Waterworks Authority officials said that they had realized
that it would be too difficult to transport water to the island by
balloon since balloons burst easily and are also expensive.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, a 108-kilometer-long pipeline will be built
to carry water from the Dragon River in Turkey's southern province
of Mersin to the island.
</P>
<P>
The government is planning to finance the project with foreign
credit.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The first Turkish bank in Russia, Yapi Kredi Moscow
(YKM), has increased its capital to 25 million U.S. dollars,
reported Turkish Daily News on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Yapi Ve Kredi Bankasi A.S. said in a statement issued here on
Tuesday that it opened its first office in Moscow in 1988 and it
founded Yapi Toko Bank with one of Russia's biggest commercial
banks Toko Bank.
</P>
<P>
Yapi Toko Bank has 5 million dollars in capital. Yapi ve Kredi
Bankasi A.S. bought out Toko Bank and changed the bank's name to
Yapi Kredi Moscow (YKM), which now has 60 employees and invests in
construction, trade and tourism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
