<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Plane Leaves Baghdad After Completing Mission </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A European airplane that landed in
Baghdad without getting prior U.N. permission departed on Wednesday
morning for Rome, Italy, after completing its mission in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The plane took off at 10:25 (0725 GMT) from the Al-Rashed
military airport in the southern suburbs of Baghdad, reported the
Iraqi News Agency (INA).
</P>
<P>
The plane, carrying three people from France and Italy, landed
at the Al-Rashed airport on Monday evening defying the decade-long
U.N. embargo on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
It was the first group that arrived in Baghdad by plane
disregarding the U.N. resolutions that require all flights to or
from Iraq must get approval from the U.N. Sanctions Committee.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tareq Aziz met the three Europeans,
one from France and two from Italy, on Tuesday and appreciated
their "brave initiative" that defied the embargo.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the delegation, Vittorio Sgarbi, member of the
European Parliament, expressed solidarity and sympathy with the
Iraqi people who have been under crippling U.N. sanctions since
1990 when Iraqi troops invaded Kuwait, said the INA.
</P>
<P>
In a declaration upon its arrival, the group termed the U.S. and
British regular unilateral bombardments against Iraq as "a
violation of international law," "acts of terrorism" and "a
genocide."
</P>
<P>
The declaration requested U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and
member states of the U.N. Security Council to intervene as soon
as possible for "the immediate and total lifting of the embargo"
and to provide emergent and effective aid for Iraq's
reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
This is the second European airplane that has arrived in Iraq
since 1990. Three years ago, British lawmaker George Galloway
arrived here by plane. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0093 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran to Respond to U.S. Overtures at Right Time: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi said here on Wednesday that Iran will respond to U.S.
overtures on improving relations at the right time.
</P>
<P>
"We will give a detailed response and at the right time,"
Kharrazi said while commenting on recent remarks of U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright, the Islamic Republic News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a joint press conference with visiting Danish
Foreign Minister Niles Helveg Petersen, Kharrazi said Iran would
not be hasty in this respect, as "haste is not good in politics and
diplomacy."
</P>
<P>
Albright last month announced the lifting of a ban on Iran's
three major non-oil exports - carpets, pistachios and caviar - and
called for a new chapter of relations with Iran.
</P>
<P>
The move came after Iranian reformists won a landslide victory
over their conservative opponents in parliamentary elections in
February, a development welcomed by Western countries.
</P>
<P>
Albright's admittance of U.S. interference in some internal
affairs of Iran in the past is an important and answerable
confession, Kharrazi said.
</P>
<P>
However, what is important is to see how the U.S. administration
will compensate for its admitted breaches of responsibility, he
stressed, adding that the Iranian government has already started
legal studies on this matter and will announce the result in time.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two countries were severed in 1980 after
Iranian students seized the U.S. embassy in Tehran and held 52
Americans hostage for 444 days in the heyday of the 1979 Islamic
revolution which overthrew the U.S.-backed Shah regime.
</P>
<P>
Since Iran's moderate President Mohammad Khatami came to power
in 1997, the two countries have softened their hostile tones toward
each other and Washington has repeatedly called for direct dialog
with Tehran.
</P>
<P>
But Iran insists that the U.S. take concrete actions to show
their sincerity in improving ties. 
</P>
