<HEADLINE> Japan's New PM Re-appoints All Cabinet Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Newly elected Japanese Prime
Minister Yoshiro Mori Wednesday re-appointed all ministers from
the cabinet of his predecessor, Keizo Obuchi, in forming his own
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet lineup was announced ahead of its formal
inauguration later in the day. The ministers were formally
appointed after an attestation ceremony at the Imperial Palace in
the evening.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet became the third in Japanese history to re-appoint
all ministers from the preceding cabinet following Nobusuke
Kishi's cabinet in 1957 and Eisaku Sato's cabinet in 1964.
</P>
<P>
Chief Cabinet Secretary Mikio Aoki said Mori decided to appoint
the ministers to their old posts "because changing ministers would
hinder Diet (parliament) business, including the deliberations of
bills."
</P>
<P>
Mori, who was elected president of the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) earlier in the day, was named by both
houses of the Diet as the new Japanese prime minister to succeed
Obuchi, who remains comatose after suffering a stroke Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mori, 62, leader of a major LDP faction, won solid majorities
in both houses of the Diet with the support of the LDP and its two
coalition partners, the New Komeito party and the newly launched
Conservative Party, which was founded by a splinter group from the
Liberal Party (LP).
</P>
<P>
One of the most pressing matters facing the Mori cabinet is the
passage of bills related to the national budget for fiscal 2000,
which is aimed at realizing economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
On the diplomatic front, Mori is expected to meet Russian
President-elect Vladimir Putin later this month and make
preparations for the July summit of the Group of Eight (G-8), to
be held in Japan's Okinawa Prefecture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
