<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Body Donation Remains Taboo in Tradition-Bound China (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The last wish of cancer-ridden Sun
Meiyan was to leave her diseased body to a dissecting room for the
purpose of medical study.
</P>
<P>
Amid profound grief, family members of the middle-aged worker
acted at her behest after she died two weeks ago. Her legacy soon
became front-page news in many Beijing newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The reason why it was news was because offering one's body
after death for autopsy research or organ transplants remains a
taboo among most Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that only 6,000 people have volunteered to be
body donors, among whom nearly 2,000 have had their wish fulfilled,
in Shanghai since the metropolis with some 14 million residents
initiated the endeavor in 1983.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 Beijing residents applied to be donors after three
local medical colleges opened special stations to accept such
donations last May. The cities of Wuhan, Nanjing and Yangzhou have
since followed suit.
</P>
<P>
Medical specialists admit that the current level of donations
can barely meet the enormous demand for organ transplants and
medical research.
</P>
<P>
At least two million Chinese lose their eyesight every year due
to cornea problems, 70 percent of whom, however, can be cured
through cornea transplant surgery.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, only 3,000 people are lucky enough to receive
the operation each year thanks to donations, according to a report
in the People's Daily.
</P>
<P>
Annually, less than 2,000 of 500,000 uremia sufferers
throughout the country receive kidney transplants, a key measure
to prolong the patient's life, leaving the majority struggling on
through time-wasting and expensive haemodialysis.
</P>
<P>
Medical academies also have a problem in carrying out post-
mortem practice due to a serious shortage of human cadavers.
</P>
<P>
Cao Chenggang, a professor at the prestigious Peking Union
Medical College (PUMC), acknowledges that many medical students
across the country have no access to cadavers, even though at the
PUMC every four students can work on one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Body Donation Remains Taboo in Tradition-bound China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Although 20 years after the modernization drive started the
Chinese people have become more open-minded, most of them still
shun the topic of body donation as a result of bred-in-the-bone
thinking that one's body is given by one's parents and can never
be destroyed before it is buried in the earth.
</P>
<P>
The adherence to tradition makes the situation of blood and
bone marrow donation formidable, too.
</P>
<P>
Some people who brave traditional opinion often encounter
prejudice or even strong opposition from family members,
colleagues and neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"It's really hard to make contributions to society after death,
" Liu Yuqing, a retiree from Wuhan University, said as he recalled
his own experience.
</P>
<P>
Another obstacle is the lack of laws to regulate the matter.
Lots of volunteers have been turned down by medical colleges for
fear of possible disputes if the donor's family declines to follow
his or her wish.
</P>
<P>
Lawmakers in Shanghai and Guangzhou are thinking about drafting
local regulations on body donation before a national law is drawn
up.
</P>
<P>
"We can learn from some foreign countries that allow the
volunteer donor to carry a donation card so that the body can be
used if the person is killed in an accident," said Professor Cao
of the PUMC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Local Regulations Issued to Prevent Domestic Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- China's Liaoning and Hunan
provinces have issued local regulations to prevent domestic
violence, and Shaanxi Province is to issue similar regulations,
according to the All-China Women's Federation (ACWF).
</P>
<P>
Northeast China's Liaoning Province issued regulations on the
prevention of domestic violence on March 8, and later the Standing
Committee of the Hunan Provincial People's Congress also approved
a decision for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of such local regulations has enriched the
laws and regulations concerning the protection of women's rights
in China, said an official of the ACWF, who added that the
regulations will also draw more social attention to domestic
violence.
</P>
<P>
The issuing of the regulations is a result of economic and
social progress in China, said Li Hui, a judge of the Supreme
Court of China. She said it is also a general trend that domestic
violence will finally be outlawed by state regulations.
</P>
<P>
There are no national regulations concerning domestic violence
in China yet, but some local governments have used other methods
such as establishing special courts to protect women's rights,
said Li.
</P>
<P>
Domestic violence is becoming rampant in some parts of the
country, especially in rural areas, nowadays, according to surveys
by the ACWF. In the past five years, about one fourth of the
complaints concerning marriage and the family which were dealt
with by the women's federation in Hunan involved domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
The regulations issued by the two provinces will unite judicial
departments and public security departments in dealing with
domestic violence by using stricter and more careful methods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
