<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iranian Reformists Push for Cabinet Reshuffle: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Iran's reformists are pressing
President Mohammad Khatami to reshuffle the cabinet by removing
ministers who are not fully cooperating with them, the conservative
daily Tehran Times said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Following the overwhelming victory in the parliamentary election
on February 18, the reformist Islamic Iran Participation Front
(IIPF) has put cabinet reshuffle on its agenda, an informed source
told the daily.
</P>
<P>
The source said that the proposed reshuffle would include Vice
President for Executive Affairs Mohammad Hashemi, Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi, Education Minister Hossein Mozaffar and
Construction Jihad Minister Mohammad Saeedi-Kiya.
</P>
<P>
The current cabinet, formed in August 1997, is a coalition of
the IIPP, the centrist Party of Constructive Executives of Iran
(PCEI) and the leftist Assembly of Combatant Clergy in Tehran
(ACC), which helped Khatami win the presidential election in 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, relations between reformists and centrists soured
before the February parliamentary election as the former strongly
opposed the candidacy of former President Hashemi Rafsanjani while
latter supported him.
</P>
<P>
Tehran Times quoted unidentified source as saying that the
reformists wanted to replace Mohammad Hashemi, Rafsanjani's
brother, with Mohammad Ali Najafi, current vice president and head
of the Plan and Budget Organization.
</P>
<P>
Both Hashemi and Najafi are members of the PCEI, which was
headed by disgraced former Tehran Mayor Gholamhussein Karbaschi.
</P>
<P>
Hashemi strongly blasted the reformists for their opposition to
Rafsanjani's candidacy before the parliamentary election. His harsh
words won conservatives' support for Rafsanjani, but caused more
people to drop their support for Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
Rafsanjani, the current chairman of the powerful advisory State
Expediency Council, barely won a seat in the parliament in Tehran
constituency.
</P>
<P>
Tehran Times named Deputy Foreign Minister for Arab and African
Affairs Mohammad Sadr and Iran's ambassador to France as the
reformists' favorites to enter the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
However, so far the IIPF, headed by Mohammad Reza Khatami, the
president's younger brother, has not officially announced any
reshuffle plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
