<HEADLINE> Arafat Meets Israeli Ministers on Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat met
Tuesday night with two visiting Israeli ministers on the latest
developments of the Middle East peace process, particularly on the
Palestinian track, the Palestinian news agency WAFA reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Arafat discussed with Israeli Minister of
Justice Yossi Beilin and Minister of Immigration and Absorption
Yuli Tamir in the West Bank town of Ramallah interim issues,
including the release of more Palestinian prisoners, said Arafat's
advisor Nabil Abu-Rudeina after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side has recently demanded Israel release 250
security prisoners while claiming that there are some 1,500
Palestinians still held in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
Beilin said he did not carry any message from Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak to Arafat and expressed his hope that a peace
agreement could be reached before the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli minister, regarded as the architect of the 1993 Oslo
Peace Accord, stressed the need for the two sides to make peace and
put an end to the decades-old conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian chief negotiator Saeb Erekat, who also attended the
meeting, affirmed that the talks were extensive and profound and
focused on the peace process.
</P>
<P>
All efforts should be exerted to reach a comprehensive peace
treaty on solving all final status issues, he added.
</P>
<P>
Led by Yasser Abed Rabbo, Palestinian chief negotiator in the
final-status talks, the Palestinian delegation will leave Wednesday
for Washington to attend Thursday's second session of the
Palestinian-Israeli talks.
</P>
<P>
The new round of talks will focus on the Israeli troop pullout
from the West Bank in the last stage and the final status issues,
including the fate of Jerusalem, border demarcation, the return of
Palestinian refugees, Jewish settlements and water sharing.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have set a May deadline to draft a framework
agreement on solving those thorny issues before reaching a
permanent peace deal by September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
