<HEADLINE> Thailand, Vietnam to Promote Tourism Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand and Vietnam have agreed
to promote travel and tourism cooperation between themselves and
within the Greater Mekong Subregion (GMS), the Tourism Authority
of Thailand said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached in a meeting between Thai Minister of
the Prime Minister's Office Praveena Hongsakul and Vietnamese Vice
President Tran Thi Thanh Thanh during the latter's recent official
visit to Thailand, the authority said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to promote bilateral tourism cooperation
and develop essential infrastructure, which is important to the
travel and tourism industry in the region, such as transportation
links, communication and human resources.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will exchange official visits to share
expertise, promote investment and undertake joint marketing and
promotion strategies. Attention will be focused on the development
of air and land links between the two neighbors.
</P>
<P>
"To establish Thailand as the natural gateway to the GMS
countries and facilitate access, more flights between the two
countries should be established," Praveena was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
There are currently 14 direct flights between Bangkok and Hanoi
every week, 17 between Bangkok and Ho Chi Minh City and three
between Bangkok and Vietnam's southern port city of Da Nang.
</P>
<P>
Praveena also hoped to promote land routes to Vietnam via Laos.
</P>
<P>
"The many new roads and bridges being built will link the three
countries in the true spirit of GMS cooperation and we foresee a
very bright future for the tourism industry in the region," she
said.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Vietnamese visitor arrivals in Thailand totaled 44,947,
down 12.46 percent from 1998, while 16,373 Thais visited Vietnam,
up 4.1 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
