<HEADLINE> Somalis Demonstrate to Back Djibouti Peace Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, April 5 (Xinhua) -- More than 3,000 people
Wednesday marched into the street of the capital city and gathered
in the municipal Stadium of Mogadishu to demonstrate their
determined support for the forthcoming Djibouti conference on the
peace in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrators from more than 26 former orphanage camps,
representing some 70,000 people in the war-torn country, have
carried placards with mottoes "force and Bullets are Not the
Solution", Unity is Strength, Separation is Disaster," "victory
for the Djibouti Conference" and others.
</P>
<P>
The streets in the capital were filled with noises of sirens,
music of Somali national anthem and thousands of jubilating
people.
</P>
<P>
All of the slogans and the speeches made in the Municipal
stadium have showed the public how Somalia's orphans are now
determined to support the forthcoming Djibouti conference.
</P>
<P>
Those orphaned people from decades long civil war are now
elderly people many of whom are famous like General Mohamed Nur
Galal, Abdi-Qasim Salad Hassan, Somalia last interior minister and
many others.
</P>
<P>
The chairman of orphans, Muse Abdulleh Mohamud who was among
the people who addressed the demonstrating people said they are
ready to defend with the last drop of their blood for the
obtaining a government for Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The chairman said, "the government has been the only parent we
had. Therefore, we should fight in reviving our parents."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, there's another demonstration, which was far
smaller in number than the Orphans, was organized by the women
groups supporting faction leader Hussein Mohamed Aidid inside a
basketball hall of Mogadishu stadium.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 people including women and children have chanted words
against the Djibouti peace conference while Hussein Aidid himself
was listening to their poems and songs.
</P>
<P>
The two opposing demonstrations in Mogadishu in the same day
have been considered as a new and positive step forward since the
people have now got their liberty of expressing their feeling over
the politics affecting the future of their children.
</P>
<P>
Similar large demonstrations have been held in Bulo Burteh,
Beletuein and Jalalaqsi districts of Hiran region since the
beginning of the week in support of the forthcoming reconciliation
conference in Djibouti.
</P>
<P>
Also, the people in Middle and Lower Shabelleh regions have
supported Djibouti President Ghelle's peace initiative for
Somalia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
