<HEADLINE> Decision to Harmonize Sharia Welcomed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The decision made by governors in
northern Nigeria to harmonize the controversial Islamic Sharia
code with extant laws was widely praised in the west African
country.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a leading Nigerian newspaper, Wednesday quoted
governor of the Southeast Abia State and Vice Chairman of the
ruling People's Democratic Party Orji Kalu as saying that the move
will get the country back on the road to achieve cohesion.
</P>
<P>
He challenged the northern governors to live up to their
promise, saying that they must put the interest of the country
first in whatever they do.
</P>
<P>
Governors of Nigeria's 19 northern states Monday resolved to
constitute a panel consisting of Muslims and Christians to
harmonize provisions of the Islamic Sharia law with the extant
penal code.
</P>
<P>
The introduction of Sharia was no pure religious decision, Kalu
said, blaming some hidden figures for trying to manipulating the
matter to find excuse for the come-back of military dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
George Igbokwe, Publicity Secretary of the Nigerian Bar
Association, hailed the decision historic on Tuesday. The northern
governors' decision vindicated President Olusegun Obasanjo's stand
that the issue be resolved through persuasion and not court
action, he said.
</P>
<P>
But he also pointed out the fact that some of the governors
didn't materialize the similar pledges made at a meeting of the
Council of State after February's nationwide clashes over Sharia,
killing some 1,000 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
