<HEADLINE> S. African Bank Announces Merger With African Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Standard Bank, a major bank
in South Africa, Wednesday announced a merger with African Bank to
improve service and enhance competition.
</P>
<P>
Standard Bank Chief Executive Officer Jack Marree told a press
conference here that the merger would better meet the need of the
mass market and provide associated insurance services.
</P>
<P>
The partnership would allow Standard Bank to expand its
financial services to the mass market more rapidly and generate
growth in the bank's accounts, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It will allow Standard Bank to optimize its existing
infrastructure more effectively and to extend its mass market
franchise whilst containing risk," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Marree, the partnership would generate an
estimated three billion rand (about 460 million U.S. dollars) in
loans within the next five years.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement of merger, Standard Bank would originate
African Bank loans through its AutoBank E and branch network,
while African Bank would originate Standard Bank E Plan accounts
through African Bank outlets.
</P>
<P>
African Bank, meanwhile, will benefit from the rapid expansion
over its private sector lending activities and an anticipated
strong growth in transactions accounts, said African Bank chief
executive officer Leon Kirkins.
</P>
<P>
The partnership would provide another strong channel for
African Bank products as Standard Bank has a well developed
private sector coverage, he said.
</P>
<P>
The mass market credit industry is South Africa's main provider
of loans to the emerging market with outstanding loans to the
value of 12 billion rand (1.84 billion U.S. dollars) per year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
