<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The English Football League are to
launch moves which could block Leeds' proposal to link up with
Nationwide Division Two side Oldham Athletic.
</P>
<P>
The Elland Road club had proposed a 50-50 initiative with
Latics, to help fund their center of excellence for an initial
five-year period.
</P>
<P>
As part of the agreement Leeds Sporting plc, who own Leeds
United, have formed a subsidiary known as Leeds Sporting Youth
Development Limited and aim to acquire a 9.9 per cent stake in
Athletic for a nominal sum.
</P>
<P>
But League spokesman John Nagle said: "The regulations
specifically state clubs cannot hold or deal in shares of other
clubs without prior written consent of the Football League.
</P>
<P>
"We have not given our consent and if necessary have the power
to prevent this from happening. All clubs must abide by our rules
and regulations. This whole issue will need to be examined and we
will be contacting Leeds and Oldham," local paper The Express
quoted him as saying.
</P>
<P>
Furious Leeds chairman Peter Ridsdale hit back by saying: "If
this was stopped from going through the only people who would lose
out would be Oldham.
</P>
<P>
"We could set up a center of excellence right on their doorstep.
Is that what the Football League really wants?" he asked. 
</P>
