<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Workers Allowed to Sell Shares of Collective Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- China now allows individual
workers to buy and sell shares of collective enterprises as the
State Administration of Taxation (SAT) asked individual workers
owning such shares to pay income tax today.
</P>
<P>
Sources from SAT said that this is the first time in history
that SAT has put forward such a requirement.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, China has begun to transform
a large number of collective enterprises around the country into
share-holding companies. In this process, it allows individual
workers to own shares of the companies, turning part of the
companies' assets into private ownership.
</P>
<P>
In a notice that it released today, SAT required individual
workers to pay income tax on dividends and proceeds from selling
such shares.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, China has nearly 1.8 million
collective industrial enterprises, which are scaled-down forms of
state-owned enterprises. Many of the collective enterprises are
township enterprises in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
China began to experiment with turning these enterprises into
share-holding companies in 1980. But it only begun to spread the
change to larger parts of the country at the beginning of this
year.
</P>
<P>
SAT did not provide any exact figure of the total amount of
additional income tax revenue that it hopes to collect after the
ownership of collective enterprises are switched.
</P>
<P>
China collected 41.4 billion yuan (about five billion US
dollars) in income tax from individuals last year, up 22 percent
over the previous year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Senior Official on Quality-Oriented Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Personal qualities should include
ethics, culture, working ability, and a sound mind and body, and
one goal of higher education should be to combine these virtues,
according to Zhou Yuanqing, vice-minister of Education.
</P>
<P>
In an article written by Zhou and published in today's
Guangming Daily, he points out that quality-oriented education is
education which improves these qualities.
</P>
<P>
China's higher education has passed through a long period from
stressing knowledge to emphasizing comprehensive quality. "Reality
has proved such truth: those who are equipped with knowledge and
strong ability cannot be called people with high quality," notes
Zhou.
</P>
<P>
The most important part of quality-oriented education is the
harmonious development of knowledge, ability, and good qualities,
which is in accordance with the goal of China's higher education:
a well-knit foundation, profound knowledge, and strong ability.
</P>
<P>
Chinese universities have been stressing quality in cultural
education since 1995 in a bid to improve university students'
cultural qualities, notes Zhou.
</P>
<P>
He also points out that stressing this aspect of education has
been beneficial to implementing the goal of quality-oriented
education among Chinese universities.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
