<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Found Aerolites, Ancient Soil at South Pole </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists found 28 pieces
of aerolites, ancient soil, and a number of samples of snow and
ice cores during China's 16th scientific expedition to the South
Pole.
</P>
<P>
The 157-day expedition ended Tuesday when the icebreaker Snow
Dragon carrying the Chinese scientists arrived at Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Ten scientists climbed up the nearly 3,000-meter-high Grove
Mountain at the South Pole, and drew world's first map of the
mountain on a scale of 1:25,000 with advanced methods including
Global Positioning System.
</P>
<P>
They found 28 pieces of precious aerolites at the mountain
region, which will help push forward the development of
cosmological chemistry and astrophysics.
</P>
<P>
Scientists say the aerolites contain much information about the
history of the solar system, and the aerolites found at the South
Pole, compared with those found elsewhere, are of greater value
because they are so well-preserved.
</P>
<P>
Prior to this expedition, scientists from Japan, the United
States, and Germany had found three aerolite-rich sites in the
Antarctic. This time, Chinese scientists discovered a fourth place
abundant in aerolites.
</P>
<P>
Chinese scientists also found ancient soil at the Antarctic for
the first time. "This finding confirms that the temperature at the
South Pole were much higher in prehistoric times than they are
today," said Liu Xiaohan, a researcher from the Geological
Institute of the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
The soil samples will be sent to laboratories for further study
of the environmental changes at the South Pole over the ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
