<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Turns Down Arafat's Request for Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese officials said the time is
not appropriate for Palestinian President Yasser Arafat to visit
Beirut, the Daily Star newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has requested to visit Lebanon for talks on the Middle
East peace process, but a welcome is unlikely without signs that
Arafat is reconciling with Syria, Lebanon's main power broker, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
"Arafat's visit is totally out of the question now. We do not
reject the principle of a visit while suitable circumstances should
be created for such a visit", the paper quoted an official as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Telecommunication Minister Imad Falouji reportedly
delivered the request to President Emile Lahoud when he was
attending a conference in Beirut. But Falouji denied the saying.
</P>
<P>
Before 1982, Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO)
made Lebanon its base from which they launched attack against
Israel. The PLO was also involved in Lebanese civil war which
erupted in 1975.
</P>
<P>
In 1978 and 1982 Israel staged large-scale invasions into
Lebanon in a bid to drive PLO out of the Arab country. Arafat and
his colleagues were forced to move to Tunisia in 1982.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Syria and the PLO turned sour after the
Palestinians signed with Israel Oslo accords that started the peace
process in 1993. Damascus insisted on a coordinated Arab stance
toward the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
So far, there are about 370,000 Palestinian refugees living in
Lebanon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Discovers World Largest Sweet Gas Field </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Oil Minister Bijan Namdar
Zanganeh announced on Wednesday that the largest sweet gas field in
the world has been discovered in southern Iran.
</P>
<P>
Zanganeh said that the independent onshore gas field has an
estimated reserve of more than 445 billion cubic meters of gas and
over 240 million barrels of liquid gas, the Islamic Republic News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Tabnak gas field with an value of about 16.5
billion U.S. dollars was discovered in the southern Fars province
by the National Iranian Oil Exploration Company (NIOEC).
</P>
<P>
The exploration work started in 1998 and so far the drilling has
reached 2,245 meters deep with a cost of 30 billion rials (about 10
million dollars at the official rate), he said.
</P>
<P>
With a proven gas reserve of 21 trillion cubic meters, Iran
ranks second in the world after Russia. It also has a share in the
world's large gas field in the Gulf which has an estimated reserve
of over 12 trillion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that Iran has drafted a 30-year exploitation
plan for the field and the production would start in the second
half of the current Iranian calendar year starting March 20.
</P>
<P>
He said that the daily production would be 1.5 billion to 2
million cubic feet or 40.5 million to 54 million cubic meters of
natural gas and 24,000 to 32,000 barrels of liquid gas.
</P>
<P>
The discovery of the gas field will help push forward the
economic development of the Fars province on the northern coast of
the Persian Gulf, Zanganeh said.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, Iran has made desperate efforts to attract
foreign investment on the "buy-back" scheme to develop gas fields
and planned to replace oil with natural gas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
