<HEADLINE> Map India Conference to Be Convened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 5 (Xinhua) -- More than 700 Indian and foreign
experts will attend a two-day conference on maps and geographic
information technologies here on April 10 and 11, the Indian
Center for Spatial Database Management and Solution (CSDMS)
announced here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The "Map India-2000" conference, jointly organized by India's
Ministry of Information Technology, Indian Space Research
Organization and the CSDMS, will discuss issues related to the
usefulness of maps and their availability in India.
</P>
<P>
The meeting is expected to come up with recommendations for
creating a liberalized national spatial data policy which is
needed to allow industry to carry out infrastructural and
developmental projects, CSDMS President M. P. Narayan told the
press here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Though India spends 20 billion rupees (465.12 million U.S.
dollars) per year on collection and management of geographic data,
maps are not easily available for the private sector," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The conference will also discuss the use of the geographical
information system, global positioning system and remote sensing
in areas like defense, telecom, power, industrial and town
planning, transportation, disaster management, mining, natural
resource management and tourism promotion, he added. 
</P>
