<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Rainfall Declines Due to "La Nina": Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's rainfall in the
current small rainy season is expected to decline in intensity as
compared with the "good" season, the Reporter newspaper quoted a
weather expert as reporting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The main factor causing the decline of rainfall in Ethiopia is
the "La Nina" phenomena that occurred in eastern and central
Pacific Ocean, the expert at the Ethiopian Meteorology Institute
said.
</P>
<P>
The dry whether over the Indian Ocean is diverting the moist
air and clouds coming to Ethiopia as result of which the Tropical
Convergence Zone could not approach the north, he said.
</P>
<P>
This has created unusual rainfall in Mozambique, while have
sucked the moist air which was supposed to approach Ethiopia, the
expert said, adding this problem might continue for some time.
</P>
<P>
The lower intensity of rainfall in the current small rainy
season could lead to poor agricultural productivity in the coming
year, according the expert. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Rebels Kill 19 in Road Ambush </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- At least 19 civilians have been
killed and another 15 wounded during a road ambush against
civilian vehicles launched by the Angolan rebel soldiers in the
northeast Lunda-norte province, official news agency Angop said
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This tragedy, one of a chain of similar events, shows that the
Angolan rebels are making effort to infiltrate into the
diamond-abundant areas for getting logistic support for their
guerrilla troops, said local analysts.
</P>
<P>
The attack took place in the Nheco area, some 47 kilometers
from the city Dundo, located in extreme northeast Angola, when the
passengers of a 12-vehicle civilian convoy were on their way to
Lucapa, capital city of the Lunda-norte province.
</P>
<P>
According to a source from the National Police, eight of the 12
vehicles were destroyed in the attack.
</P>
<P>
Lunda-norte is famous for its abundant diamond reserves, which
has long- term supported the Angolan rebels led by Jonas Savimbi
for staging the civil war against the government troops.
</P>
<P>
After the Restauro Operation launched by the government troops
at the turn of the year, the rebels have been driven out of major
cities. But they scattered into small groups and resorted to
guerrilla warfare.
</P>
<P>
Local analysts said that the rebels, whose logistic support had
been cut off, need the precious stone for continuing the guerrilla
war.
</P>
<P>
In late March, 15 people died on the Xamacola/Muxinda road in
Capenda Camulemba municipality, as their vehicle hit a landmine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
