<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Southeast States Renew Call for Confederation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Governors of Nigeria's Southeast
region Tuesday renewed their calls for confederation, according to
This Day, a leading Nigerian newspaper Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Achike Udenwa, chair of the governors' forum
in the region and governor of Imo State as saying that they would
pursue the matter from the constitutional point of view.
</P>
<P>
He said that the only way to douse the present tension in the
country is to adopt a confederation system, adding that
federation is by no means the break-up of the country.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the statement by President Olusegun Obasanjo last
month and some there prominent Nigerians that the call was
unpatriotic, Udenwa said that they were "not well advised" on the
matter.
</P>
<P>
He said the call truly reflected the "mood of grassroots
easterners", and would prevent the country from disintegrating if
implemented.
</P>
<P>
President Obasanjo last month dismissed the agitation for
federation or a national sovereignty conference as "highly
unpatriotic", and called on politicians to contribute to the
strengthening of a strong and united country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
