<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Coulthard: I'll Be Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Formula one driver David Coulthard
has refused to write off his championship chances, despite being
kicked out of the Brazilian Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
The 29-year-old Scot fell 20 points behind Ferrari's Michael
Schumacher, after McLaren lost their appeal, on Tuesday, against
Coulthard's disqualification from second place in Sao Paulo.
</P>
<P>
But with 15 races still to come, Coulthard believes his title
dream is still alive and plans on launching his fightback in the
heart of Ferrari territory in Sunday's San Marino Grand Prix at
Imola.
</P>
<P>
"They have not won the championship yet and we are not going to
give it to them," Coulthard said.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to fight hard all the way. We can turn things
around and that is what we are going to do. We have a quick racing
car, we are going to a circuit which I like and where I have gone
well in the past and we want to take the challenge to Ferrari and
show them we still believe we have the best car," he said.
</P>
<P>
Coulthard, who along with team-mate Mika Hakkinen who is still
searching for his first point, won at Imola in 1998 and badly
needs to repeat the feat this weekend with Schumacher having won
both of the opening races.
</P>
<P>
The International Court of Appeal in Paris rejected McLaren's
claim that the bumpy nature of the Interlagos track caused the
front wing of Coulthard's car to become illegal.
</P>
<P>
The five-man panel said the Woking-based team should have taken
account of the difficult surface as their rivals had done.
</P>
<P>
"I went to Paris with what I felt was a very strong case,"
Coulthard said.
</P>
<P>
"But we will not allow this to have any affect on team morale.
</P>
<P>
"I have been around in Formula One for a few years and McLaren
have obviously been around much longer and there is always ups and
downs when you are competing. We have that every two weeks and we
are well used to being able to deal with things, put them behind
us and handle the facts," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
