<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Stick to "One China" Policy: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Thailand will stick to the "one
China"policy and make it a basis for the further development of
friendly and cooperative relations with China, Thai Prime Minister
Chuan Leekpai said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Chuan, also leader of the ruling Democrat Party, made the
remarks when meeting with a delegation of the Communist Party of
China (CPC) led by Dai Bingguo, member of the CPC Central
Committee and head of the International Liaison Department of the
CPC Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
Thai-Chinese relationship has always been good both in the
governmental and non-governmental aspects, Chuan said, adding that
the relationship has now been expanded to the party-to-party level.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that the new relationship will help further promote
mutual understanding and cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister also expressed gratitude to China for its
support extended to his country during the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Dai expressed the hope that the friendly and cooperative
relationship between China and Thailand will be further
strengthened after this visit.
</P>
<P>
The delegation, which arrived here Monday, met three local
party leaders Tuesday, including Chart Thai leader Banharn Silapa-
Archa, deputy Democrat leader Banyat Bantadtan and Chart Pattana
leader Korn Dabbaransi.
</P>
<P>
The delegation is paying a five-day visit as the guest of Surin
Pitsuwan, Thai foreign minister and a member of the Executive
Committee of Thailand's Democrat Party.
</P>
<P>
The trip is aimed at enhancing relations between the CPC and
political parties in Thailand.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the delegation will hold talks with Prime
Minister Chuan and leaders of Thailand's ruling and opposition
parties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
