<HEADLINE> DPRK, Japan Begin Normalization Talks in Pyongyang </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The Democratic People's Republic
of Korea (DPRK) and Japan started their ninth round of talks here
Wednesday over normalizing of diplomatic ties between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
A Japanese official, who asked not to be named, told reporters
after the morning session that the DPRK delegation "called for
settling of the historical account, and sought apology and
compensation" from Japan.
</P>
<P>
Jong Thae Hwa, who heads the DPRK's delegation, was quoted as
saying, "All our people are closely watching the talks, and we
want to lead the talks to success in line with their hopes."
</P>
<P>
Kojiro Takano, who leads the Japanese side, repeated Japan's
apology, but again rejected any compensation during the session
this morning.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK delegation declined to comment on the talks.
</P>
<P>
This round of talks is expected to last three days, to be
followed by two more rounds scheduled for Tokyo and then Beijing
or another country.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK and Japan began their normalization talks in the late
1980s, with eight round of talks held before they were suspended
in 1992. 
</P>
</TEXT>
