<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Fall in Tokyo on Wall Street Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices fell in Tokyo Wednesday,
dragged down by high-priced information and technology issues
which were dampened by Tuesday's decline on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 132.16 points, or 0.64
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 20,462.77.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, dropped 19.24 points, or 1.12 percent, to 1,
695.05.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section edged up to 744.87 million shares
from Tuesday's 742.37 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Oil distributor Japan Energy was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Information and technology issues faced selling, while
brokerage houses were the biggest losers, declining 5.53 percent.
</P>
<P>
Wholesalers, air transportation firms and nonferrous metal
makers were also weak.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, electric power and gas firms were strong, reflecting
a downward trend in crude oil prices,
</P>
<P>
Nonlife insurers, rubber makers and marine transportation firms
also saw gains.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers narrowly
outnumbered gainers 632 to 614, with 146 issues closing unchanged.
</P>
</TEXT>
