<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Radioactive Waste Arrives in Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The first load of radioactive
nuclear waste arrived Wednesday morning at Mol in the Belgian
Province of Antwerp, which met with protests by dozens of people
against the dangerous transport.
</P>
<P>
The shipment came by train from the nuclear recycling plant of
La Hague in northern France. The container with 400 kilograms of
vitrified nuclear waste will be loaded onto a truck and taken to
the nearby town of Dessel for storage.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the Belgian government had agreed to a first shipment
of nuclear waste from the reprocessing plant in France to Mol.
</P>
<P>
Environmental organization Greenpeace and three Belgian towns,
Mol, Geel and Dessel, who said last week they would ban the
transport of the highly toxic waste on their territories, failed
to obtain a court injunction stopping the transport for security
reasons.
</P>
<P>
In another Belgian town Dendermonde, the planned transport of
highly radioactive nuclear waste was successfully stopped by a
judge, who stopped the train on the territory of the town in the
Province of East Flanders.
</P>
<P>
The judge agreed with an injunction of Greenpeace that relevant
safety measures were inadequate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
