<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police Likely to Recommend Closing Weizman File </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli police are inclined to
end the criminal investigation against President Ezer Weizman for
receiving large sums of money from a French businessman between
1988 and 1993, Israel Radio reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the police have not yet decided on what grounds they
will recommend that the file be closed. Lack of evidence, absence
of guilt and offenses no longer subject to prosecution due to the
statute of limitations are the three possibilities that could back
the police to close the file.
</P>
<P>
The police are expected to formulate their recommendations by
the end of the week and transfer the file to the Attorney-General's
Office and the State Prosecutors Office for a final decision.
</P>
<P>
The investigation against Weizman was touched off by
investigative reporter Yoav Yitzhak on December 30, 1999. Yitzhak
said in a press conference that Weizman had received some 453,000
U.S. dollars from Edouard Saroussi in monthly payments of various
accounts.
</P>
<P>
The money was allegedly deposited into a trust account managed
by a mutual friend of Weizman and Saroussi, attorney Hanina
Brandes, and from there the money was moved to accounts held by
Weizman and his family members.
</P>
<P>
Yitzhak also claimed that Weizman had not reported this income
to the income tax authority and that he had also allegedly violated
a law that forbids public servants from receiving gifts.
</P>
<P>
On January 12, 2000, Attorney-General Elyakim Rubinstein and
State Prosecutor Edna Arbel ordered a police "examination" of the
allegations. Five days later, following the discovery of a document
showing that Weizman and Saroussi had maintained unreported
business connections, they upgraded the examination into a full-
fledged criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
However, it later emerged that their business connection had
terminated before Weizman began to receive the money, thus ruling
out a possible bribery charge. The investigation therefore focused
on possible tax violations and a possible breach of the gift-taking
clause of the Public Service Law.
</P>
<P>
A senior judicial source said that whatever tax violations there
may have been were technical in character and did not warrant an
indictment.
</P>
<P>
Weizman's office refused to comment on this issue Wednesday,
saying only that the president will accept whatever the police have
recommended.
</P>
<P>
Weizman has been questioned by the police investigation team
several times and he repeatedly told the police that the money he
received was from a close family friend and the money has been used
mainly for recovering his son's health who was badly injured during
the Israeli-Egyptian war.
</P>
<P>
Weizman also said that there was a political motive behind the
allegations and he would probe that even after the case was over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Turkish Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news items
in leading Turkish newspapers on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Daily News:
</P>
<P>
-- Turkish President Suleyman Demirel said on Tuesday that as a
European force, Turkey had proved the importance of its
contribution to stability and security in the region during and
after the Cold War period.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks upon 51st anniversary of foundation of North
Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), which Turkey has been part of
since 1952.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the European Security and Defense Initiative (ESDI)
which may exclude non-EU NATO members, Demirel said that "with its
contributions, it is clear that Turkey must be involved in every
security organization that will be founded in Europe."
</P>
<P>
Milliyet (National):
</P>
<P>
-- Recai Kutan, the leader of the main opposition Islamist
Virtue Party said on Tuesday that ratification of the
constitutional amendment for Demirel's second term in office will
be "quite difficult" in the second round vote to be held on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that his party would vote against the bill unless
it is appended with an article which making party closures more
difficult if not impossible.
</P>
<P>
Hurriyet (Freedom):
</P>
<P>
-- Two F-16s of Turkish Air Force crashed into ground near
Yildizeli township of central Sivas province late on Tuesday during
flight training.
</P>
<P>
Rescue teams found one pilot alive and continued to search for
the two others. Sources said that the pilots ejected themselves
before the crash.
</P>
<P>
The fighter planes took off from the Fifth Main Jet Base
Commander, an air base in Amerzifon township of Amasya province in
Black Sea region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
