<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Doctors Toughen Sanctions for Higher Wage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Doctors in Israel's public sector
have stepped up their sanctions Wednesday, following Tuesday's
fruitless negotiations between Treasury wage officials and the
Israel Medical Association (IMA).
</P>
<P>
Due to the strike, which entered its 20th day Wednesday, all
public general, psychiatric, geriatric and rehabilitation hospitals
stopped working except the function of emergency rooms, intensive
care units and delivery rooms.
</P>
<P>
In addition, diagnostic institutes and mini-surgical theaters in
community health fund facilities also shut down, while salaried
specialist physicians stopped receiving patients in health fund
clinics.
</P>
<P>
Also on strike are doctors in the Health Ministry's district
health offices, family health centers, school physicians and
doctors working in all government ministries.
</P>
<P>
The IMA is struggling for a new wage contract that will restore
the amount of money lost by erosion since the old contract expired
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The IMA has asked the Treasury for statistical analyses of wage
offers or to calculate the economic effects of a change in wage
structure. IMA Chairman Yoram Blachar claims the Treasury is
willing only to give the doctors a 5 percent raise across the
board.
</P>
<P>
"The impression is that the Treasury is not willing to advance
negotiations but merely aims to tire the doctors out without
solving the problem," he told the Israel Radio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan told Israeli Foreign
Minister David Levy that he plans to help Israel implement U.N.
Security Council Resolution 425, while they were meeting in Geneva
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Levy briefed Annan on Israel's preparations for the upcoming
withdrawal from south Lebanon and told Annan that if the U.N plans
to assist in the implementation of Resolution 425, it will find
Israel to be a willing partner.
</P>
<P>
Annan indicated that the current U.N. Interim Force in Lebanon
would work to maintain quiet when Israel redeploys to the
international border with Lebanon. He added that the sides would
find a way to avoid violence and general deterioration in the
situation in the zone.
</P>
<P>
Ha'aretz:
</P>
<P>
-- Former U.S. President Lyndon Johnson and Secretary of State
Dean Rusk, worried about a threat of nuclear proliferation in the
Middle East, pressured Israel in the mid-1960s to promise not to
develop nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
But the strategy failed, with a White House emissary sent to Tel
Aviv reporting back to Washington that Israel is a tougher
bargainer than the former Soviet Union, then archenemy of the
Americans.
</P>
<P>
Israel refused to make a commitment it considered dangerous to
its national security, according to classified documents released
Tuesday by the State Department historian's office.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- In the most volatile day ever for U.S. stocks, the Nasdaq
composite index and the Dow Jones industrial average each plunged
more than 500 points Tuesday before reversing course as buyers
flooded back into the battered market.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Israeli investors confound fears that the local
bourse would similarly suffer sharp losses and pushed stock prices
even higher.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip Maof 25 index gained 1.25 percent to 505.81, while
the Tel Aviv 100 index rose 1.02 percent to 498.91. Even the
Teltech index of local technology companies, which is widely
believed to be more vulnerable to developments on Nasdaq, rose 1.5
percent.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- Eli Yishai, chairman of the ultraorthodox religious Shas
party, Tuesday gave National Police Chief Yehuda Wilk a letter
written by Shas spiritual leader Rabbi Ovadia Yosef.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, Yosef comments on his March 18 diatribe against
Education Minister Yossi Sarid in the course of a sermon in a
synagogue, which is being investigated by police.
</P>
<P>
Yosef repeated for the fifth time in the letter that he did not
intend to incite violence against Sarid.
</P>
<P>
The letter was Yosef's own initiative and it is possible that
police will accept it as testimony, sparing the rabbi from
questioning in the case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
