<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reform Under Review in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's top government
officials and representatives of donor countries and international

financial institutions began a two-day quarterly meeting here
Wednesday to review the reform in the country.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that the meeting will provide us with the rare
opportunity to evaluate together the results of the tremendous
efforts of the royal government of Cambodia during the past year,"
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who is presiding over the meeting, said in
his opening speech.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time, we will be able to draw experiences and
lessons from the government's action. This evaluation will be used
to develop action plans and new measures aimed at pushing forward
the momentum that has been successfully established," Hun Sen
added.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the government will discuss 10 topics and
will for the first time deal with the government's new anti-
corruption and good governance measures. Other topics include
military demobilization, civil administration reform, forestry
management, fiscal reform and social sector issues.
</P>
<P>
Donor countries have urged Cambodia to take serious measures to
deal with corruption and establish good governance.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the World Bank and the government are now
preparing a good-governance action plan to be submitted to the
Consultative Group meetings in Paris next month.
</P>
<P>
This is the third quarterly donors' meeting after the
Consultative Group's gathering in Tokyo in February 1999 to
monitor and follow up the Cambodian government's implementation of
reform programs.
</P>
<P>
The last meeting was held here on October 27 in Phnom Penh.
</P>
</TEXT>
