<HEADLINE> Philippines Hopes to Become Rice Exporter by 2003 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph Estrada
said Wednesday that he is confident that the Philippines can
attain rice sufficiency by 2002 and even become an exporter of the
commodity by 2003.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview, the president assured the people that his
administration would see to it that every Filipino family has
enough food to eat by the time he steps down from office in 2004.
</P>
<P>
"This is what we are focusing on. Perhaps by 2003, we would be
the one to export rice. We are working hard so that our food
security program would ensure that no Filipino goes hungry in his
own land," the president said in Filipino.
</P>
<P>
He said this will be realized through his administration's
continuing efforts to modernize the agriculture sector, which
includes tapping the assistance of the International Rice Research
Institute.
</P>
<P>
Food security is one of the president's five centerpiece
programs, alongside mass housing, peace and order, the fight
against graft and corruption, and electoral reforms.
</P>
<P>
The president said that aside from the record-high yields of
the agriculture sector last year, his optimism that the country
could achieve food sufficiency was further boosted by new
initiatives aimed at increasing rice production in small farms.
</P>
<P>
These, he said, include the propagation of hybrid seeds,
similar to those used in China, Vietnam and Thailand, which will
increase the present national average of paddy yields from 2.9
metric tons per hectare to 6 to 10 metric tons per hectare.
</P>
<P>
The agriculture sector expanded by over 6.5 percent in 1999 and
is expected to sustain this momentum with a growth rate of 3 to 4
percent this year.
</P>
<P>
Over 40 billion pesos (1 billion U.S. dollars) has been
allocated under this year's national budget for programs and
projects in the agriculture sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
