<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Woo More Tourists From West Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Culture, Arts and
Tourism Minister Abdul Kadir Sheikh Fadzir is leading a tourism
promotion team to seven countries in West Asia in an effort to woo
more Arabs to visit Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
During the working visit from April 5 to 19, the team will
visit Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the United Arab Emirates (UAE),
Bahrain, Oman, Egypt and Qatar, according to Bernama news agency
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time that Malaysia has carried out tourism
promotion activities in West Asia. Last year, the minister toured
Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, the UAE to promote the country as a tourist
destination.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has targeted to attract 200,000 visitors from the Gulf
countries by the end of this year, compared with 23,000 visitors
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the target, the Culture, Arts and Tourism Ministry
has decided to form a task force each in Dubai of the UAE, Kuwait
City in Kuwait and Jeddah in Saudi Arabia to look after and
coordinate Malaysian tourism promotion activities.
</P>
<P>
The culture and arts section of the Malaysian embassies and
consulates general in those countries has also been reactivated to
support and spearhead tourism promotion activities or initiatives.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also plans to set up a regional tourism office in
Dubai to help Malaysia attract travelers and tourists from the
Gulf states and their neighbors.
</P>
<P>
On the schedule of the tourism minister's current trip are
meetings and discussions with the Malaysian embassies in the
countries concerned, dialogue sessions with chief executive
officers of travel agencies and Malaysian multinational
corporations, Bernama said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
