<HEADLINE> Some Spaniards Visit Kanungu Last Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan security sources have
revealed that some Spaniards last year visited Kanungu in
southwestern Uganda where over 530 people of a cult were burnt to
death in a church fire on March 17.
</P>
<P>
State Minister for Security Muruli Mukasa, appearing before the
 parliamentary committee on presidential and foreign affairs on
Tuesday, said that the information was provided by local
residents.
</P>
<P>
Investigations are being conducted to establish the motive of
the visit, the minister was quoted by Wednesday's New Vision
daily as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Movement for the Restoration of Ten Commandments of God was
held responsible for the death of over 920 Ugandans revealed by
the police so far. The leaders of the cult are said to be on the
run.
</P>
<P>
Previous reports here quoted police sources as saying that the
cult had received donations from some Western countries like
France, Germany, Italy, Austria and Spain. The donations were
mainly from individuals.
</P>
<P>
However, the police have not yet established the motive of the
donations and how the donations were spent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
