<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Market Responsible for Tanzanian Fuel Price Hikes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by Zhang Dacheng
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Recent fuel price hikes in
Tanzania arose from oil price hikes in the world market and the
Tanzanian government should not be blamed, a senior World Bank
official has said.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's newspapers here quoted World Bank country
representative James Adams as saying that Tanzania's oil sector
has already been liberalized and the government could no longer
determine the market prices.
</P>
<P>
"There are issues which are within the government's control,
but the recent raising of fuel price was worldwide and would
affect not only Tanzania but many other countries on the
continent," he said.
</P>
<P>
He admitted that the recent fuel prices hikes would further
increase the already high cost of doing business in the country
compared with other countries in East and Southern Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, Adams noted that some of the taxes charged by the
government on fuel are too high and needs further streamlining.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania currently imposes six different taxes on imported
petroleum products, including import duty Tanzania Petroleum
Development Corporation margins, processing fees, Road Toll,
Excise Duty, Energy Fund and Windfall Profit tax. In addition,
there is city services levy for Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian oil marketing companies have been complaining that
the government levies and taxes were behind the unpredictable
escalating prices of petroleum products, saying that all these
taxes were approximately 150 percent above the landed prices.
</P>
<P>
The consumer of the products would not enjoy anything from the
liberalization of the oil sector unless world prices drop
drastically, they said.
</P>
<P>
The fuel prices in Tanzanian pump stations last Monday rose to
a historic high, the ninth over the past few months, inflicting a
heavy blow on local consumers.
</P>
<P>
The prices of super petrol and diesel were raised by 20
Tanzanian shillings (one U.S. dollar equals 802 Tanzanian
shillings at present) up to 565 and 518 shillings per liter
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The frequent increases of fuel prices have caused serious
worries among Tanzanian transporters.
</P>
<P>
If not checked, the upward trend would cause untold sufferings
to the end-users in Tanzania as it would paralyze the sector, an
engine for national economic growth, they said.
</P>
<P>
Permanent Secretary in the Ministry of Finance Peter Ngumbullu
said last week that the treasury was contemplating to review
petroleum products price structure to ensure that fuel is sold to
consumers at realistic and affordable prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
