<HEADLINE> Ten Percent Blood Donors in Dar Hospital Tested HIV Positive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- One out of ten Tanzanians
volunteering to donate blood at the largest hospital in Dar es
Salaam were found to be HIV positive, the African newspaper
reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a medical study conducted by the Muhimbili University
College of Health Sciences, it was revealed that 522 out of the
6,000 people who lined up for blood donation at the Muhimbili
Medical Center (MMC) last year were tested positive for HIV.
</P>
<P>
According to the study, HIV was the most prevalent cause for
blood infection, accounting for 8.7 percent of blood donation
cases at the center.
</P>
<P>
Much of the blood donated is meant for anaemic children
patients under the age of five and the screening work is vital to
avoiding the risk of an acute HIV infection, the report said.
</P>
<P>
In the countrywide, the demand for blood infusion has risen to
180,000 cases per year. Earlier, the situation at the MMC blood
bank was reported to have deteriorated to the extent that certain
blood groups were completely missing.
</P>
<P>
The HIV/AIDS infection rate in Tanzania, a country with an
estimated population of 30 million, is said to be around 10
percent. Most of the victims are in the age group of 16 to 40.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing Delivers Fewer Jets in First Quarter Due to Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Boeing Co., the largest
aircraft maker in the world, Tuesday said it delivered 50 fewer
jetliners than planned in the first quarter because of delays
caused by the 40-day strike by engineers and technical workers.
</P>
<P>
Boeing had planned to deliver 125 jets, but actually only
delivered 75 jets in the first quarter. News release from the
aircraft giant said 33 jets were delivered in January but a strike
by the Society of Professional Engineering Employees in Aerospace
trimmed February deliveries to 27 and March shipments to 15.
</P>
<P>
"It's great to have our engineering and technical team back.
Though we have work to make up, our planned commercial deliveries
for 2000 are less than the record output of last year," said
Boeing Chairman Phil Condit.
</P>
<P>
But Boeing still plans to deliver about 490 jetliners by year's
end as projected, down from last year's record 620, the company
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
"There will be some impact in the first quarter, maybe in the
second quarter, but nothing to change our margins for the year,"
said company spokesman Larry McCracken.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Boeing also delivered 26 military aircraft in the
first quarter, including three C-17 transports, 14 fighter jets,
two Apache helicopters, one Chinook helicopter, four training jets
and two Delta II rockets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
