<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Outstanding Mainlanders Given Work Permits in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 5 (Xinhua) --Three residents of Shenzhen in
south China's Guangdong Province have been given permits to work
in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The three, Mu Shicheng, Ren Zengyuan and Feng Youmin, are the
first group of Chinese mainlanders to be given work permits since
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) initiated a
program last December to introduce more large-caliber talent into
the region, according to the Guangdong Provincial Public Security
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, Hong Kong-registered companies can submit
applications to the SAR government for the employment of mainland
personnel. The SAR government will sign and issue entry permits to
those who are hired, as well as to their spouses and children
under the age of 21.
</P>
<P>
Mu Shicheng has a doctorate in engineering and has been
awarded a special allowance by the State Council for his
outstanding achievements in mechanical engineering research. He
was also named a honorary senior engineer by the Siemens Company
of Germany.
</P>
<P>
Ren Zengyuan is engineer-in-chief of the Guangsha Recording
Equipment Co. Ltd. of Shenzhen, and Feng Youmin is an engineer
with the Xingqing Electronic Company of Shenzhen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
