<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumers Cautioned Against Sub-Standard Cosmetics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese consumers are being
cautioned against smuggled and fake overseas cosmetic products
because these substances may lead to skin problems.
</P>
<P>
They are advised to examine the labels on imported products,
such as a CCIB (China Commodity Inspection Bureau) mark or the new
CIQ (China Inspection Quarantine) mark which is issued by the
State Administration for Entry-Exit Inspection and Quarantine,
along with the dates of production and expiration, and the
instructions in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Chinese are expected to spend 32.2 billion yuan (about 3.88
billion U.S. dollars) on cosmetics this year, and in rich areas,
imports are always favored even though the prices are often much
more than for domestic products.
</P>
<P>
However, the beauty industry has been hurt by smuggled, sub-
standard, and even fake cosmetics, according to a report in today'
s Guangming Daily which said that about 80 percent of imported
commodities on the shelves in south China's Guangdong Province
were found to be sub-standard during an official inspection.
</P>
<P>
Specialists with the administration said there are many quality
problems among those products, such as the use of banned additives,
and over-the-limit amounts of heavy metals and bacteria.
</P>
<P>
An eight-year study conducted by doctors at the Hebei Medical
College suggested that some imported cosmetics, especially hair
dye, can cause pathological changes in the skin, including
allergic reactions and cancer, the report said.
</P>
<P>
China's quarantine authorities have also tightened the quality
control and supervision of exported cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration for Entry-Exit Inspection and
Quarantine will authorize a group of institutions to examine the
claims on product labels, including hygiene standards and
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
Local branches of the administration have been asked to
intensify the inspection of cosmetic imports and exports, and
products failing to meet standards may be confiscated and
destroyed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
