<HEADLINE> Internet Challenges China's Traditional Economy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The rapid growth of the Internet
industry in China will have an enormous impact on China's
traditional economy, said Song Ling, director of the Information
Promotion Department of the Ministry of Information Industry in
Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
"Innovation has been a powerful engine of economic growth in
the new era," said Song. Official statistics showed that by the
end of last year, there were 520 Internet Service Providers (ISPs)
in China, while Internet Content Providers (ICPs) exceeded 1,000.
</P>
<P>
"A number of Chinese enterprises and institutes are aware of
the Internet's potential and are taking active measures to get
online," Song said.
</P>
<P>
For instance, Legend, the country's top computer manufacturer,
has already announced that it will shift its business focus to the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
China's leading household electric appliances makers such as
Hai'er Group and the TCL Group are now adopting new marketing and
management strategies on the Internet.
</P>
</TEXT>
