<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fireworks Producers, Dealers Punished </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A total of 118 Chinese have been
fined or kept in custody during the latest nationwide campaign
against the illegal production and sale of fireworks.
</P>
<P>
Police have examined 870 licensed fireworks plants in seven
provinces including Hebei, Jiangsu, and Zhejiang, closing more
than 80 plants which were found to have serious safety problems.
</P>
<P>
The police also shut down 547 illegal factories, 593
unauthorized retailers, and 274 materials manufacturers, while
confiscating their products and equipment.
</P>
<P>
Thirteen offenders were detained and the other 105 people were
fined.
</P>
<P>
In the wake of several massive explosions at fireworks plants,
the State Council and the Ministry of Public Security issued a
circular last week ordering immediate action against the illegal
production and sale of fireworks.
</P>
<P>
The most deadly recent explosion occurred on March 11 at a
privately owned firecracker factory in a village near Pingxiang in
East China's Jiangxi Province, killing 33 people and injuring 12
others.  
</P>
</TEXT>
