<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Seals Spotted in East China's Liaodong Bay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese fishermen reported seeing
hundreds of seals near Liaodong Bay in the northeast Bohai Sea
over the past winter.
</P>
<P>
Zoologists said there were 2,000 to 3,000 seals spending this
winter at Liaodong Bay as a result of the improved marine
environment in the region.
</P>
<P>
Some 30 young seals were caught by fishermen and then sent to
the local aquaculture department, where some were confirmed as
harbor seals, an animal under state-level protection.
</P>
<P>
The seals swim from north to south from December to May every
year to reproduce, and Liaodong Bay is the southernmost
reproduction site for harbor seals in the world, zoologists say.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of the 1980s, harbor seals were abundant at
Liaodong Bay, and about 2,000 to 3,000 harbor seals could be found
there every year.
</P>
<P>
Because the seals prey on a large amount of fish, the fishermen
were encouraged to hunt them at that time. In addition, marine
pollution accelerate the falling number of seals.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, local departments have been urged to improve
the marine environment, and in 1992 a state-level nature reserve
for harbor seals was set up in the port city of Dalian on the bay.
Seal hunting has been forbidden since then, and the public is now
more aware of protecting this sea animal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
