<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Stops Iraqi Oil Fleet in Gulf Waters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Iran's Islamic Revolutionary Guards
have stopped a fleet carrying smuggled Iraqi oil in the Persian
Gulf, the official Islamic Republic News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It quoted an unidentified source as saying the elite corps
marine patrol found on April 1 an oil fleet, registered in
Honduras, and ordered it to anchor.
</P>
<P>
The fleeting, named "al-Masroo," was carrying 2,500 tons of
smuggled oil from the Iraq, the source said. It is now in the
waters off the southern coast of Iran, with its 18 crew members
under the command of Captain Qassem Abdul Qader, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, the report did not give more details about the
incident, nor did it reveal the destination of the fleet.
</P>
<P>
Relations between the two neighbors again soured in the past
months as they accused each other of sheltering rebel groups which
carried out terror attacks in both Tehran and Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, under U.N. sanctions since its 1990 invasion of Kuwait,
has been banned from selling its on the open market. Starting from
1996, it was allowed to sell limited amounts of oil under the U.N.
oil-for-food program to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian
supplies for its 22 million people.
</P>
<P>
But the United States and its allies has repeatedly accused
Baghdad of smuggling refined oil out of its Basra and Abu Flus
ports.
</P>
<P>
A Multinational Interception Force has been patrolling the Gulf
since 1990 to make sure tankers don't violate the sanctions. But
its
ships and aircraft can only patrol international waters in the
center of the Gulf, thus leaving the door open for oil smugglers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
