<HEADLINE> Australian Exports Rise in 1999 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Australia saw a turnaround in its
trade last year following the East Asian economic crisis although
it still suffered a 980 million U.S. dollar deficit.
</P>
<P>
A government's trade statement for 1999 issued Wednesday shows
a rising trend of total exports in each of the last eight months
of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Trade Minister Mark Vaile said the positive trend continued in
January and February this year.
</P>
<P>
Services and manufacturing exports each increased by 6 percent,
with transport equipment up 22 percent due to a strong growth in
passenger vehicle exports.
</P>
<P>
Despite the export recovery later in the year, total goods and
services exports dropped by 0.4 percent to 69.1 billion U.S.
dollars for the year.
</P>
<P>
Treasurer Costello said Wednesday that the strengthening world
economy will bring its advantages for Australia.
</P>
<P>
"It means that our exports will find better prices and better
volumes," he was quoted by AAP as saying. 
</P>
