<HEADLINE> S. Africans to Witness Trio of Planets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 4 (Xinhua) -- South African stargazers have
a rare opportunity to see planets Jupiter, Saturn and Mars
together shortly after sunset on Thursday, the South African
Astronomical Observatory said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Viewers looking towards the north-western horizon will see
Jupiter, the brightest of the three planets, directly below the
moon, and Mars slightly below and to the right of Jupiter, the
observatory said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Saturn will be to the right of the moon, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The best time to spot the planets will be between 20 and 30
minutes after sunset.
</P>
<P>
"All three planets and the moon will be quite low in the sky
even then. By an hour and a half after sunset, they'll be below
the horizon," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
