<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Opposition Leader Charged with Stealing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Secretary General of
Tanzania's opposition Civic United Front (CUF) Seif Sharif Hamad
and seven others Tuesday appeared in a regional magistrate court
in Zanzibar, being charged with stealing with violence, the
Guardian newspaper reported on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Reading charges against Hamad and his colleagues, the
prosecutor, Inspector of Police Aziz Juma, alleged that the
accused attacked members of the Police Force viciously and were
involved in the theft of a sub-machine gun with 10 rounds of
bullets last Sunday evening.
</P>
<P>
He said that several policemen who were attacked by the accused
 sustained serious injuries and were admitted to Mnazi Mmoja
hospital.
</P>
<P>
All the accused were released on a 28 million Tanzanian
shillings (about 35,000 U.S. dollars) bail bond and the case was
adjourned until 18 April.
</P>
<P>
The CUF, Tanzania's main opposition party, refuses to recognize
Zanzibar President Salmin Amour's 1995 election in which Hamad
lost by less than 1 percent amid allegations of ballot-rigging.
</P>
<P>
Authorities in the Indian Ocean archipelago have been accusing
Hamad's party of hatching a scheme to oust Amour after the vote.
</P>
<P>
Though it joined with Tanganyika to form the nation of Tanzania
in 1964, Zanzibar is a semiautonomous state with its own
government and parliament. 
</P>
