<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Continues to Ban Pyramid Schemes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- China began a three-month campaign
this month to ban the long-prohibited pyramid schemes, which have
staged a comeback recently in some places in the country.
</P>
<P>
A circular released by the State Administration of Industry and
Commerce requires that local administrations at various levels
keep a close watch on all kinds of pyramid-type sales, especially
those in disguised form.
</P>
<P>
Notoriously fraudulent pyramid sales were abolished by the
State Council, China's cabinet, when it issued the "Notice on
Prohibition of Pyramid Sales" in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
"However, such schemes in disguised forms, such as sales in
chain stores and via the Internet have popped up again, and seem
to be spreading fast," said an official with the administration.
</P>
<P>
Pyramid schemes deceive people into buying things, mostly fake
products, and have caused severe damage. Some of them in disguised
form even promote superstition among sales personnel, posing a
threat to social order and stability.
</P>
<P>
"These lucrative and quick-yielding schemes have lured many
into fraud and their revival will be severely dealt with," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
