<HEADLINE> Kenya to Import Maize to Fight Hunger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Kenya will import three million
bags (90 kgs per bag) of maize by September this year to fight
the looming hunger in some parts of the country due to severe
drought.
</P>
<P>
Kenyan Agriculture Minister Chris Obure made the remarks in the
capital Nairobi Tuesday when he launched this year's Freedom From
Hunger Walk aimed at promoting food security, which is scheduled
for May 20, Kenya media reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
He said his government had no other alternative other than to
import the cereals to recover the shortfall before next harvest.
</P>
<P>
Obure said persistent drought in North Eastern and Eastern
Provinces and parts of Central Province has brought about
agonizing moments for many households and poses a serious
challenge to his ministry and the government.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the country's National Cereal and Produce
Board had " substantial commercial stocks of maize" which was
being off-loaded as famine relief under the direction of the
Office of the President.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the World Food Program (WFP) office in Nairobi has
launched an emergency appeal for 43.4 million U.S. dollars to
feed hungry Kenyans in the next three months as over 75,000 tons
of food is urgently needed for an estimated 2.7 million hungry
Kenyans.
</P>
<P>
WFP Information Officer Lindsey Davies said statistics gathered
earlier in the year indicated that more people are at risk of
starving in the east African nation than has been reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
