<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yoshiro Mori Named Japan's New Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Yoshiro Mori, newly elected
president of Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), was
elected Wednesday new Japanese prime minister by the Diet (
parliament).
</P>
<P>
Mori, 62, who was elected the LDP president earlier in the day,
gained 335 of the 488 valid votes at a plenary session of the 500-
member House of Representatives with the support of the LDP and
its two coalition partners, the New Komeito party and the newly
launched Conservative Party, which split from the Liberal Party (
LP).
</P>
<P>
In the 252-member House of Councilors, Mori garnered 137 of 244
valid votes.
</P>
<P>
Mori, leader of a major LDP faction, succeeded ailing Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi to become Japan's 55th prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi has been in a coma after suffering a stroke Sunday.
</P>
<P>
All cabinet ministers are to be retained under the new premier,
and the Mori cabinet will be launched in the evening after an
imperial attestation ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the three ruling coalition parties are then
scheduled to hold talks to confirm their policy accords, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
The Mori cabinet is expected to strive toward passing bills
related to Japan's national budget for fiscal 2000 so as to seek
an economic recovery, and to push for a successful July summit of
the Group of Eight (G-8) most industrialized nations in Okinawa
Prefecture, in line with the policies of Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
After being elected the LDP head, Mori told a meeting of the
LDP lawmakers held at party headquarters that he will strive to
get the Japanese economy back onto a growth path. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
