<HEADLINE> No Change in Obuchi's Condition: Acting Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- There is no change in the condition
of Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, who has been in a coma
since Sunday after suffering a stroke, acting Prime Minister Mikio
Aoki said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"There has not been any change in the prime minister's
condition since yesterday," Aoki told a news conference Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Aoki denied remarks by a senior member of the ruling Liberal
Democratic Party (LDP) that Obuchi is showing "signs of recovery."
</P>
<P>
"That has not been confirmed. We have heard from the hospital
that the premier's condition has not changed," Aoki said.
</P>
<P>
Tamisuke Watanuki, leader of the LDP's Obuchi faction,
reportedly told fellow faction members that Obuchi's brain waves
were fine and his hands were moving, after he visited Obuchi at a
Tokyo hospital on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi was hospitalized early Sunday after suffering a stroke
at his official residence. He was moved to the hospital's
intensive care unit and put on a respirator after his condition
worsened Sunday night. 
</P>
