<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0258 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: On-line Share Trading Brings Little Benefit Without Tech Support By Ou Sa and Chen Yu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Many stock brokers in Hong Kong
have launched on-line share trading service since no more than two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
However, the service, which implies efficiency and low cost,
will disappoint customers without technological support, experts
said.
</P>
<P>
"Many stock brokers in Hong Kong claim they can offer such kind
of service," said Douglas Chen, chief executive officer of SHK
Online, an Internet venture of Hong Kong's Property giant, SHK Co.
Ltd.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to the fact that many Internet stock trading
services in Hong Kong are only E-mail based systems -- whereby a
brokerage staff, after receiving a client's order via the Internet
or a closed computer system, still needs to manually post that
order on the market system for execution.
</P>
<P>
Confirmation, settlement and several other steps in processing
the order also have to be handled manually by the broker with such
systems.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, brokers who are not participants of the Hong Kong
Stock Exchange will need to pass on the order to an Exchange
participant for execution.
</P>
<P>
In such cases, on-line dealing is not very different from
traditional ways of placing orders by phone, fax or in person.
</P>
<P>
By August this year, when the Exchange is expected to launch
the third generation of the automatic order matching and execution
system (AMS/3), the Internet orders can be directly fed into the
Exchange's trading system without manual input.
</P>
<P>
But still, "without a highly automatic system, the broker
cannot enable the customers to enjoy the benefit of AMS/3, which
has the capacity of handling one order each second," said Felix
Miao, deputy chief executive officer of the CASH on-line, Inc.
</P>
<P>
What really influences the speed of processing an order hinges
on the broker's own system rather than the Exchange's system,
according to Miao.
</P>
<P>
CASH on-line, Inc. a member of the Celestial Asia Securities
Holdings Limited CASH), is looking forward to the launch of the
AMS/3, which will be able to remove the last manual step in its on-
line share trading system.
</P>
<P>
Technology is equally important for other means of trading
stocks.
</P>
<P>
With an advanced on-line trading system and the launch of AMS/3,
using Internet terminals instead of telephones, the account
executives in the broker's branches can help conduct trade for
their clients more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
But experts said that even if all the brokers in Hong Kong
could provide on-line share trading service with necessary
technology back-up, the business will still be just one of the
forms of serving people's investment needs and cannot replace
other ways of trading, especially trading at branches, in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
First, people have their own preference to choose the way of
trading. The special personal environment at branches where people
can communicate with the account executives and other investors
face-to-face cannot be duplicated on-line.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, the gap between the cost for on-line and other forms
of trading stocks is not wide in Hong Kong right now.
</P>
<P>
On-line share trading has a huge room of growth with about 1.7
million Internet users but there are fewer than 16,000 on-line
stock trading users currently in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
CASH, being the first participant of the Exchange to open on-
line service, has planned to spend 70 million HK dollars (about
nine million U.S.dollars) investing in technological development
this year.
</P>
<P>
SHK Online has set up recently partnership with the U.S. on-
line broker Web Street Securities to develop services of on-line
trading of U.S. securities for Hong Kong people.
</P>
<P>
Tai Fook On-line Services Limited, which jumped on the wagon no
more than three months ago, has just set up an e-wealth club for
its on-line services users to promote the business.
</P>
<P>
"We have to invest in technology, we have to upgrade, we have
to identify more and more ways to serve as many people as possible,
otherwise, we cannot survive," said CASH's Miao. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
