<HEADLINE> Foreign Agencies Fund Sri Lanka's Road Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Several foreign agencies have
pledged to fund a major highway project in southern Sri Lanka to
develop the hinterland through speedy transport, said an official
report published on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Development Bank has agreed to provide a loan of 89.4
million U.S. dollars for part of construction of the 128 km
Southern Express Highway, said the report.
</P>
<P>
The highway, to cost 296.2 million dollars, will be built
between Kottawa, an inland town 20 km southeast of the capital
Colombo, and Matara, a southern coastal city 160 km southeast of
Colombo.
</P>
<P>
The Japan Bank for International Cooperation (JBIC), Swedish
International Development Agency (SIDA) and the Nordic Development
Fund (NDF) will co-finance 128 million dollars, said the report.
</P>
<P>
It said the balance 78.8 million dollars will be met by the Sri
Lankan government.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary design work has been completed and boundary line
marking is in progress.
</P>
<P>
The project, to begin in October 2000 and be completed in 2005,
will be implemented by the Road Development Authority. 
</P>
</TEXT>
