<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: ADB, Bangladesh to Strengthen Cooperation in Poverty Alleviation By Chen Jian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Asian Development Bank (ADB)
President Tadao Chino's three-day visit to Bangladesh ended
Tuesday. During his stay, the ADB and Bangladesh signed a Poverty
Reduction Partnership Agreement, which will help further
strengthen the cooperation between the two sides in poverty
alleviation.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, which is the first of its kind signed by
the ADB with a developing member of the bank, Bangladesh became a
model country to implement the ADB's new Poverty Reduction
Strategy first, which signifies the importance the ADB attaches to
the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the Bangladeshi government will
strive to achieve universal primary education by the year 2010,
and reduce maternal and infant mortality rates by 75 percent and
65 percent respectively by 2010.
</P>
<P>
It also aims to lower the proportion of malnourished children
by 40 percent by 2010, and make reproductive health services
available to all women of appropriate age by that year.
</P>
<P>
To support these goals, the ADB plans to lend up to 500 million
U.S. dollars annually to Bangladesh. Most of the loans will be on
a concessional basis subject to resource availability and country
performance.
</P>
<P>
The ADB assistance will support poverty reduction through
interventions in agriculture and rural development, primary health
and nutrition, basic education, water resource management, road
and rail transportation, power and energy, urban development and
the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The assistance will promote the three pillars of the ADB's
poverty reduction strategy: pro-poor economic growth, social
development and good governance.
</P>
<P>
The ADB president, while briefing newsmen here Tuesday, said
the ADB, as the largest multilateral provider of development funds
for Bangladesh, has extended 132 loans to the country, totaling
nearly 6 billion dollars, and grants for 257 technical assistance
projects, totaling 156 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Chino praised the government's micro-credit policy,
particularly the poverty alleviation program during his talks with
Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina. He lauded various reform measures
adopted by the government in the economic sector and appreciated
the government's proper tackling of the 1998 floods.
</P>
<P>
Hasina asked the ADB president to consider the objective
situation of a country while making any reforms, expressing the
hope that the ADB would take into consideration her government's
programs for poverty reduction.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Chino also held talks with some civil society
representatives. Speaking at a meeting with the Bangladesh
Federation of Chambers of Commerce and Industry, he said his bank
has initiated a new private sector development strategy, promoting
the creation of enabling environment, generation of business
opportunities in the private sector and extension of catalytic
support to private sector projects through fund providing.
</P>
<P>
The ADB is committed to further strengthening the development
partnership between the two sides for the overarching goal of
poverty reduction, Chino said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0263 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "One Country, Two Systems" Successful in Hong Kong, Tung Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TORONTO, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) of China, said
here Tuesday that Hong Kong has made a success of the concept of "
one country, two systems."
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has met two challenges "almost simultaneously" since
the handover in 1997. "The first was political, and that was how
to make a success of the untested concept of 'one country, two
systems'," Tung told more than 900 guests at a business luncheon
in the Metro Toronto Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
"Anybody who has been to Hong Kong since the handover can see
that 'one country, two systems' has been transformed from a
concept into an everyday reality," he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is working well. We have been given maximum support from
our national leaders. At the same time, it has been made clear
time and again, that it is up to us in Hong Kong to chart our own
course," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Our political structure is evolving in accordance with the
provisions of the Basic Law," which provides a constitutional
framework for the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, Tung
said.
</P>
<P>
In addition to high-profile constitutional cases, hundreds of
thousands of cases are dealt with in the same way as before the
handover every year, according to the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong also takes pride in meeting the second challenge, "
that was how for Hong Kong to achieve a recovery from the longest
recession in our history brought upon us by the Asian financial
crisis," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
In two successive budgets, Hong Kong introduced tax cuts and
freezes or reductions in government fees and charges as a means to
encourage consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
"We also decided to proceed with massive investments in
infrastructure such as roads, railways and schools, not only as a
means to stimulate the economy but also as a way to build a better
future for our community," he said.
</P>
<P>
With the recovery of the regional economy in Asia, and the
strength of economy in North America, Hong Kong's economy is now
rebounding strongly, Tung told the gathering.
</P>
<P>
For the fourth quarter of 1999, Hong Kong's economy grew at an
impressive rate of 8.9 percent and the growth rate is forecast at
5 percent for the year 2000, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are proud of what we have achieved in almost three years
since reunification," Tung said.
</P>
<P>
He believes "Canada and Hong Kong have always had a special
relationship."
</P>
<P>
About 100 Canadian companies have branches or subsidiary
operations in Hong Kong, while another 450 are represented by
distributors, agents or joint ventures, according to the chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
"You have almost 3 billion Canadian dollars (about 2.1 billion
U.S. dollars) worth of investments in Hong Kong," he told the
guests of the luncheon hosted by the Canadian Club of Toronto, the
Hong Kong-Canada Business Association and Hong Kong Toronto
Development Council.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong is seeking cooperation in developing clean transport,
where "Canada looks to have some of the most promising technology,
" said Tung.
</P>
<P>
He also identified education for a knowledge-based economy and
dealing with the sewage and waste as areas where Hong Kong should
look to "places like Canada" for ideas and inspiration.
</P>
<P>
This is Tung Chee Hwa's first visit to Canada in the capacity
as the chief executive of HKSAR.
</P>
<P>
Tung arrived here Saturday to begin a four-day visit to Canada.
He said he had "a wonderful visit" and would take with him "a very
happy memory" of Canada.
</P>
<P>
Tung is scheduled to leave for the United States Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
