<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yoshiro Mori Elected New Japanese Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Yoshiro Mori, newly elected
president of Japan's ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), was
elected Wednesday new Japanese prime minister by both houses of
the Diet (parliament).
</P>
<P>
Mori, 62, who was elected LDP president earlier in the day,
succeeded ailing Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi to become Japan's 55
th prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi has been in a coma after suffering a stroke Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mori, leader of a major LDP faction, was elected prime minister
by a wide margin at plenary sessions of both houses with the
support of the LDP and its two coalition partners, the New Komeito
party and the newly launched Conservative Party.
</P>
<P>
All cabinet ministers are to be retained under the new premier,
and the Mori cabinet will be launched in the evening after an
imperial attestation ceremony.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the three ruling coalition parties are then
scheduled to hold talks to confirm their policy accords, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Mori, who got to know Obuchi when they were studying at a
university in Tokyo, has been a staunch supporter of Obuchi and
has helped strengthen the party's ties with New Komeito.
</P>
<P>
He was named LDP secretary general in 1998 when Obuchi took
office as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Before becoming secretary general, Mori served as LDP General
Council chief and the party's top policy-maker.
</P>
<P>
From 1983, Mori served many posts in the Japanese cabinet such
as education minister, international trade and industry minister
and construction minister.
</P>
<P>
A native of Ishikawa Prefecture on the Japan Sea coast, Mori
joined the Sankei Shimbun, a leading Japanese daily, in 1960 and
has been elected to the House of Representatives 10 times since
1969.
</P>
<P>
Mori and Obuchi have known each other since the late 1950s when
they belonged to a debating club at Waseda University in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Mori's influence in the LDP has grown as the party has placed a
high priority on maintaining a solid working relationship with New
Komeito, one of LDP's coalition partners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
