<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Handover Ceremony Hall in Macao Might Be Preserved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A group of architectural specialists
are assessing the solidity of the hall in which the Chinese and
Portuguese governments held the ceremony for Macao's power
transfer on December 20 last year.
</P>
<P>
The assessment is conducted in response to the public appeal
that the historic structure should be preserved well permanently.
</P>
<P>
Over the past several months, streams of tourists and local
residents have flocked to the site to relish the atmosphere of
that solemn historic event which became a turning point for Macao.
Portuguese rule in Macao ended and the Macao Special
Administrative Region (SAR) of China was founded right after the
handover ceremony.
</P>
<P>
From January 28 up to March 28, the hall had accommodated the
presents given to the Macao SAR by China's provincial governments
and the Hong Kong SAR government. The presents were given to
celebrate Macao's return to the motherland. During the two months,
as many as 220,000 people visited the hall and viewed the presents
with admiration.
</P>
<P>
With the conclusion of the exhibition, the SAR government
invited some architectural specialists from the inland areas of
China to study the feasibility of permanent preservation of the
hall.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with a Sino-Portuguese agreement, the hall had
been designed to be a temporary building and would be disassembled
after the handover ceremony. However, the steelwork and ceiling
were made solid enough to ensure the security of heads of states
of both countries and dignitaries from around the world.
</P>
<P>
Initial assessment showed that the hall's steelwork and ceiling
do not pose significant safety problems, but part of the walls and
floor might need replacement or reinforcement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
