<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yoshiro Mori Says Predecessor's Policy to Be Pursued </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Yoshiro Mori, the newly-elected
president of the Japan 's ruling Liberal Democratic Party (LDP),
said he will continue to pursue outgoing Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi's policy of economic revitalization.
</P>
<P>
He made the remark right after his election by LDP lawmakers
of both houses of the Diet (parliament) Wednesday. He is set to be
picked as the country's new prime minister in the Diet at 1 p.m. (
0400GMT) to succeed ailing Obuchi.
</P>
<P>
Mori, a close ally of Obuchi, expressed the hope for Obuchi's
earliest recovery.
</P>
<P>
Mori also vowed to make every effort toward achieving victory
for the LDP in the upcoming lower house election, which must be
held by October when the term of current lower chamber members
expires.
</P>
<P>
Mori, 62, leader of a major LDP faction, is certain to become
Japan's 55th prime minister as he has secured the support of all
LDP factions as well as LDP's two coalition partners, the New
Komeito party and the newly launched Conservative Party.
</P>
<P>
As LDP head, Mori is expected to appoint Acting Secretary
General Hiromu Nonaka to the party's No. 2 post of secretary
general, and Hidenao Nakagawa, a former Science and Technology
Agency chief,as acting secretary general, LDP sources said.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi was hospitalized early Sunday after suffering a stroke.
He was later moved to the intensive care unit of a Tokyo hospital
and has been in a coma since then. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
