<HEADLINE> Xinhua World Economic Summary at 0450 GMT, April 5 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States has sent its first direct
shipment of meat to China's market in line with new rules Beijing
has formulated to carry out a farm agreement signed last year.
</P>
<P>
The shipment of meat, which departed from San Francisco on a
plane bound for Shanghai on Sunday night, "represents the first
direct opening of China's market to U.S. meat and poultry
producers," said U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky. (
US Meat-China)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. government on Tuesday accused Mexico and
several other nations of erecting unfair barriers to keep American
telecommunication companies out of their markets.
</P>
<P>
The administration set deadlines for later this year for the
barriers to be removed and raised the prospect that cases would be
brought to the World Trade Organization (WTO) if the most
objectionable barriers are not dealt with. (US-Mexico-Threat)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MANILA -- Philippine Globe Telecom and Nokia have signed an
agreement valued at 170 million U.S. dollars for the expansion of
Globe's Global System for Mobile communications (GSM), Philippine
News Agency said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is the seventh major agreement that Globe has
entered into with Nokia, one of the world's leading mobile phone
suppliers, bringing the total investments between the two
companies since 1994 to approximately 300 million dollars. (
Philippines-Commerce)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- A group of fast growing chip makers expects chip
demand to grow in double-digits for the next two years due to
communications boom, The Wall Street Journal reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Fabless Semiconductor Association, a group of 240 chip
companies that don't own their own factories, expects demand for
chip wafers, the underlying materials from which chips are made,
to increase 39 percent in 2000 and 48 percent in 2001. (US-Chip)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LOS ANGELES -- Microsoft's rivals applauded a federal judge's
ruling Monday that the world's largest software maker violated
antitrust laws by trying to monopolize the Web browser market.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts believe U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson's ruling that Microsoft violated the Sherman Antitrust Act
by tying its Web browser to its operating system and changed the
competitive landscape in Silicon Valley. (US-Microsoft)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazil registered in the first quarter of this
year a surplus of 26 million dollars, said Ministry of Development,
Industry and Foreign Trade on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A positive balance came about from exports for 12.48 billion
dollars going over imports by 12.22 billion dollars, said the
Ministry. (Brazil-Surplus)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
YANGON -- Myanmar has exempted collection of transit fee on
goods for fellow member countries of the Association of Southeast
Asian Nations (ASEAN), according to the latest issue of the local
Business journal.
</P>
<P>
The exemption was to take effect as from February 1 this year
on goods carried through prescribed route in accordance with the
ASEAN Framework Agreement on the Facilitation of Goods in Transit,
the Business journal quoted a recent announcement of the Myanmar
Commerce Ministry. (Myanmar-ASEAN) 
</P>
