<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NEWSMAKER: Japan's New Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Yoshiro Mori, a journalist-turned-
politician, on Wednesday was elected by the Diet (parliament) to
succeed ailing Keizo Obuchi to become Japan's new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Mori, 62, who got to know Obuchi when they were studying at a
university in Tokyo, was named secretary general of the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) in 1998, when Obuchi took office as
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Mori has held a number of positions within the LDP and the
government.
</P>
<P>
Before becoming secretary general, Mori served as LDP General
Council chief and the party's top policy-maker.
</P>
<P>
From 1983, Mori served many posts in the Japanese cabinet such
as education minister, international trade and industry minister
and construction minister.
</P>
<P>
A native of Ishikawa Prefecture on the Japan Sea coast, Mori
joined the Sankei Shimbun, a leading Japanese daily, in 1960 and
has been elected to the House of Representatives 10 times since
1969.
</P>
<P>
Mori and Obuchi have known each other since the late 1950s when
they belonged to a debating club at Waseda University in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Mori's influence in the LDP has grown as the party has placed a
high priority on maintaining a solid working relationship with New
Komeito, one of LDP's coalition partners.
</P>
<P>
Mori, head of the LDP's fourth largest faction, has been a
staunch supporter of Obuchi and has helped strengthen the party's
ties with New Komeito. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
