<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Bomb Kills One Old Man in Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 4 (Xinhua) -- An old man was killed in Nis on
Tuesday by a cluster bomb left over from NATO attacks last year,
adding to the worry that NATO bombs are still threatening lives of
Yugoslav people although the war ended nine months ago.
</P>
<P>
The 70-year-old Vladimir Jovanovic, a resident of the southern
Serbian city of Nis, was working in his garden when he
accidentally activated the bomb with a shovel, the media reported.
</P>
<P>
His son told reporters that a large number of cluster bombs
were dropped by NATO aircraft during its air strike on Nis last
May, and those which did not explode are now scattering in this
area. The son added that his father helped a team in search of the
unexploded bombs last autumn as a guide.
</P>
<P>
Local government officials said some bombs remained unnoticed
despite the efforts made by police and troops to clear the bombs
left over in the war. Police in Nis warned local residents to stay
away from the scene of explosion. They promised to conduct
thorough search for more unexploded bombs as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
NATO launched attacks against Yugoslavia on March 24 last year.
During the 78-day-long attack, NATO sent out more than 1,100
warplanes and dropped some 25,000 tons of explosives in 25,200
sorties or more, killing over 2,500 civilians and injuring more
than 10,000 others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E-mail Users Increase rapidly Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, April 4 (Xinhua) -- The number of electronic
mailboxes soared 83 percent in 1999, reaching 569 million by the
end of last year, a study by a U.S. information service company
Messaging Online shows.
</P>
<P>
The study predicts that if e-mail accounts continue to increase
at this rate, they will outnumber both telephone and television
accounts in the next two or three years.
</P>
<P>
Of the 569 million e-mail boxes, 333 million are in the United
States, taking up about 60 percent of the total. The study says
two thirds of the workforce in the United States now uses e-mail
and one fourth of the U.S. families have at least one e-mail box.
</P>
<P>
On average, U.S. families have four e-mail boxes per household.
"It is apparent that e-mail is a new mass communications channel,"
said Messaging Online in a report, estimating that at least 40
percent of Americans use e-mail.
</P>
<P>
The study also shows that e-mail is still in an early stage of
development in countries other than the United States, although
the number of e-mail boxes rocketed 100 percent last year,
increasing from 117 million at the end of 1998 to 236 million.
</P>
<P>
A decade ago, there were only 15 million e-mail boxes in the
entire world. Since then, however, e-mail technology has spread
into both business sectors and households at a dramatic speed,
changing their ways of communication. The study shows that Webmail
and ISP online are the most popular categories of e-mail with 170
million and 149 million mailboxes in use respectively by the end
of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
