<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ministry Official Rules Out Cattle Disease in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- An official with the Ministry of
Agriculture today confirmed that it was "impossible" for the
Chinese hay to spread the food-and-mouth disease (FMD) which was
found in Japan and the Republic of Korea (ROK).
</P>
<P>
China had banned imports of cattle, sheep, pigs and other
products from Japan and the ROK immediately after the outbreak of
the highly-contagious disease, and related departments have
enhanced monitoring and control efforts, said Wang Changjiang with
the Animal Quarantine Division.
</P>
<P>
"Judging from the hay drying and processing procedure in China,
it is impossible to spread the FMD through imports of hay, " Wang
said, adding that the ministry has so far not received any reports
of FMD outbreaks.
</P>
<P>
Corresponding to allegations from Japan and ROK that Chinese
hay may have transmitted the disease, Wang said "the rumor was
simply not true."
</P>
<P>
China has implemented a permit-granting system for fodder
industry to supervise animal feed procedures and processors, today
's China Daily quoted another ministry official as saying.
</P>
</TEXT>
