<HEADLINE> hke040504--Indonesian Prosecutors to Take Further Action Soeharto </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian Attorney General's
Office (AGO) was dissatisfied with the results of Monday's probe
into former president Soeharto's alleged corruption, the
Indonesian Observer reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We will evaluate the results of Monday's probe and determine
what actions to take regarding Soeharto," Head of the AGO's Sub-
directorate of Corruption Crime Antasari Azhar was quoted by the
newspaper as saying.
</P>
<P>
Six investigators from the AGO on Monday questioned Soeharto
for one and a half hours at his house in Central Jakarta, but the
session had to be halted when his blood pressure went up.
</P>
<P>
The probe was done at his home after Soeharto twice failed to
appear when officially summoned by the AGO. His lawyers cited
health grounds on both previous occasions and argued that his
speech was impaired.
</P>
<P>
The investigating team said the 78-year-old Soeharto responded
well to most of the questions, and that they planned to quiz him
again once they receive a report from doctors present during the
session.
</P>
<P>
"We'll see whether the team would go to the suspect's residence
or ask him to appear at the Attorney General's Office. It's up to
the medical team's advice," Antasari added.
</P>
<P>
Separately, spokesman for the AGO Soehandoyo said his office
had not set a schedule to resume the questioning as of Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Attorney General Marzuki Darusman himself will announce the
date and the details of the resumption of the investigation," he
was quoted by the Jakarta Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was named as a suspect in a case of alleged corruption
during his 32-year-rule after Marzuki Darusman decided to reopen
the case in December last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
