<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Unemployment Rate Likely to Remain High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's high rate of
unemployment, now officially at about 17 percent, will remain the
country's main problem until 2010, according to Manpower Minister
Bomer Pasaribu.
</P>
<P>
"We won't be able to overcome the unemployment problems for
another five to 10 years," Bomer was quoted by the Indonesian
Observer Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
Bomer said 36 million Indonesians are now out of work as a
result of the prolonged economic crisis, while the workforce has
increase by 3.5 million since the onset of the financial turmoil
in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
With this year's economic growth estimated at just between 3
percent and 4 percent, only 1.6 million jobs can be created, he
said.
</P>
<P>
To reduce unemployment, Bomer said, Indonesia should continue
to send workers, especially skilled ones, to other countries.
</P>
<P>
"We should open an international market for (Indonesian)
workers," he said.
</P>
<P>
About 400,000 Indonesian workers are sent abroad annually,
mainly to the Middle East and Asia Pacific countries. The number
of Indonesians working abroad on contracts currently stands at
about 2 million.
</P>
<P>
The government earns about 500 million U.S. dollars annually
from the remittances of overseas workers.
</P>
<P>
"If we could send 400,000 Indonesian workers abroad, we could
send one to two million workers in the future and the country
could obtain 2 billion U.S. dollars," the minister said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
