<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American, Caribbean Commission Stresses Poverty-fighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, April 4 (Xinhua) - The 25th Session of the
Economic Commission for Latin America and the Caribbean (ECLAC)
Tuesday highlighted the need to fight poverty in this region.
</P>
<P>
In a report entitled, "Equality, Development and Citizenship,"
the commission said that overcoming poverty constitutes an ethical
and political challenge, adding that social policies should make
more considerations for the poor.
</P>
<P>
The more appropriate programs are those of a comprehensive
nature and long duration, and programs centered on preventing
poverty from being passed on from generation to generation, said
the document.
</P>
<P>
Education and employment are two "master keys," and only when
people in this region achieve these basic fundamental supports,
can they meet this challenge, the document stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to ECLAC studies, at least 11 years of education are
required to make it possible for one not to fall into poverty.
</P>
<P>
ECLAC, a United Nations' commission founded in 1948 to co-
ordinate policies for the promotion of economic development in the
Latin American region, normally meets every two years in one of
the Latin American capitals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
