<HEADLINE> Financial Sector: Shenzhen's Major Tax Source </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Rapid economic development has
turned the financial sector of the city of Shenzhen in south China
's Guangdong Province into a major source of tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics released recently by the Shenzhen Local
Taxation Bureau, the financial sector turned in 13.8 billion yuan
in taxes from 1995 to 1999 at an annual growth rate of 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen is one of the two cities in China with a stock
exchange, and the development of the securities market has also
promoted the growth of banking and insurance services in the city.
</P>
<P>
The city is now home to 55 domestic financial organizations, 31
overseas-backed financial and insurance businesses, 203 securities
brokers, and 70 insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
There are about 200 overseas-backed financial organizations in
China, and these along with insurance companies are given a range
of preferential treatment, including tax holidays in their early
years of operations.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen is the first in the nation in profits generated from
the assets owned by overseas-backed financial and insurance
businesses. The assets of overseas-financed financial
organizations in Shenzhen account for 20 percent of the national
total, while their profits make up 40 percent of the country's
total. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0306 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Professor Develops Anti-Drought Agent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 5 (Xinhua) -- A special agent which can absorb
and store water 500 even 3,000 times the weight of a single seed
can help to battle the scourge of drought.
</P>
<P>
The agent, developed by Prof. Wang Shuyu of the Northeast
Agricultural University in this capital of Liaoning Province, can
be mixed with seeds before insemination. It will serve as a "mini-
reservoir" when the seeds germinate.
</P>
<P>
Years of testing have proved that the germination rate can be
raised to around 95 percent from 50 percent when this special
agent is used on farmland with only 10 percent of all the water
needed for plant growth.
</P>
<P>
Farmer Chang Fuyuan of Santaizi Village only spent one yuan (12
US cents) more per mu (one fifteenth of a hectare) when he planted
corn last year, and he harvested nearly 2,000 kg more of corn than
usual.
</P>
<P>
Prof. Wang believes that use of the agent can greatly reduce
the losses caused by drought, as 53.3 million ha of farmland in
China are of the dry farming type. Besides, China is facing a
growing problem of desertification.
</P>
<P>
The agent has been used in 62 arid counties in northeast and
north China since last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0307 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1.8 Kilometer Railway Bridge in Northeast China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENYANG, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Construction work has begun on a
1.8-kilometer-long bridge on an electrified passenger railway line
from Qinhuangdao, a port city in north China's Hebei Province, to
Shenyang, capital of northeast China's Liaoning province.
</P>
<P>
Workers will build 64 piers and two abutments to support the
bridge, which will span seven local rail lines, according to
railway authorities.
</P>
<P>
Work on the high-tech bridge is scheduled for completion in
July 2001.
</P>
<P>
The new Qinhuangdao-Shenyang railway line will be double
tracked with a total length of 404.64 kilometers, and can
accommodate speeds up to 160 kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
Listed as one of the country's key projects, the new line will
cost 15 billion yuan, which will be fully covered by the
government and completed and commissioned in August 2003.
</P>
<P>
The new railway will alleviate the serious congestion of
freight transport in northeast China, and will help double the
region's railway freight volume, said one expert with the Shenyang
Railways Administration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
