<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tax-free Deposit Offered for Education Expenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The People's Bank of China (PBOC)
has decided to allow financial institutions, except postal outlets,
to take tax-free deposits from citizens to be earmarked for their
children's education expenses.
</P>
<P>
The central bank entitled banks to give individual savings
accounts on preferential terms, and give yields on interest that
are excluded from a 20-percent tax levy imposed last November,
according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The move is expected to help people save money for their
children's non-compulsory education in senior high school and
college, and promote higher education in China, the paper says.
</P>
<P>
The Industrial and Commercial Bank of China was previously the
only bank designated by PBOC to conduct the business last year,
and this was welcomed by Chinese complaining about much lower
interest rate and the tax levy.
</P>
<P>
Depositors, limited to fourth-graders in elementary school or
older, can open education savings accounts on one-year, three-year
or six-year terms by using real names.
</P>
<P>
The minimum amount for opening such an account is 50 yuan (6 U.
S. dollars) and the total amount must be under 20,000 yuan (2400 U.
S. dollars), the PBOC said.
</P>
<P>
Upon withdrawals of the deposits, the depositor must present
credentials provided by his or her school to get the 20 percent
tax exemption.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
