<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0313 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pets Contribute to Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Pets may grow into a significant
aspect of the Chinese economy, as the small animals are boosting
domestic consumption by costing Beijing residents 500 million yuan
a year, according to the Beijing Association for the Protection of
Small Animals.
</P>
<P>
The association's statistics show that two-fifths of Beijing
households keep an average of 1.2 pets, which might be dogs,
cats, birds, fish or even insects. The city has 1.6 million of
such pets.
</P>
<P>
If people spend 300 yuan a year on one pet, the total cost in
Beijing for this hobby would be 500 million yuan, the association
calculated.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that, with an aging society and more people
becoming affluent, raising pets has become more and more popular.
Many supermarkets sell pet food and pet toys in addition to their
ordinary goods.
</P>
<P>
However, for health and safety reasons, some restrictive
regulations still pose an obstacle to the development of the pet
trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
