<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Opposes U.S. Certification in Drug-Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian President Fernando
Henrique Cardoso Tuesday defended the necessity for multilateral
control in fighting drug-trafficking, but opposed any form of
certification granted unilaterally by "a single country."
</P>
<P>
He is referring to the United States as a single country.
</P>
<P>
"We're in favor of multilateral cooperation. But we don't
believe any country can serve as a single judge in a matter of
such complexity," he said at a press conference after meeting
Costa Rican President Miguel Angel Rodriguez, referring to a
procedure applied annually by the United States to certify the
appropriate behavior for drug-fighting countries.
</P>
<P>
Brazil backed up the international penal tribunal being created,
he added, "But we don't think this matter can be changed for the
interest of just one country."
</P>
<P>
The demand of the United States has caused friction between
this country and states in Latin America, especially Mexico and
Colombia, where the question of drug-trafficking is particularly
sensitive.
</P>
<P>
President Cardoso arrived here Monday night to begin a three-
day state visit to Costa Rica. 
</P>
</TEXT>
