<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru's Fish Exports Rocket in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 4 (Xinhua) -- Peru's fish exports in the first
quarter of this year reached 263.3 million U.S. dollars, up 33.4
percent compared to the same period in 1999, figures from the
National Fishing Society (SNP) show.
</P>
<P>
SNP figures show that fish meal exports in the first quarter
hit 193.4 million dollars, soaring 58.1 percent over the same
period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Exports of frozen and fresh refrigerated fish and seafood came
second with 30 million dollars, followed by fish oil with 24.7
million dollars, which represents 14.5 percent more than that in
the same quarter in 1999.
</P>
<P>
In preserved fish and seafood, SNP estimates 13.3 million
dollars were exported, 11 percent less than the first three months
of last year.
</P>
<P>
The total fishing production for the first quarter amounted to
734,500 tons, up 89 percent over the same period in 1999, among
which 557,000 tons or 75.8 percent was fish meal, up 101.7 percent
as against the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
SNP President Juan Ribaudo said Tuesday that despite the
falling prices on the world market, the country's target to exceed
1 billion dollars in fishery exports this year will be fulfilled.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
