<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Stresses Foreign Policy of Detente and Dialog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Majlis (parliament) Speaker
Nateq Nouri on Wednesday stressed the importance of detente and
dialog in developing relations with foreign countries.
</P>
<P>
Iran is seriously following the policy of detente and
constructive dialogue with other countries to develop ties based on
mutual respect, non-intervention in others' internal affairs and
observation of international regulations, Nouri said.
</P>
<P>
In a meeting with visiting Danish Foreign Minister Niels Helveg
Petersen, he said Iran is willing to improve ties with other
countries, especially Denmark and the European Union (EU), the
Islamic Republic News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Nouri called for exchanges of political and parliamentary
delegations between Iran and Denmark to expand bilateral relations
and remove disputes.
</P>
<P>
However, he criticized the so-called selective and double-
standard behavior of EU states and certain international
organizations toward terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The EU members claim their opposition to terrorism but in
practice they have supported in various forms the terrorist group
Mujaheddin Khalq Organization (MKO) which has assumed
responsibility for its crimes such as mortar attacks on residential
units in Iran, Nouri said.
</P>
<P>
An opposition group based in Iraq, the MKO has long been engaged
in activities against the Iranian government.
</P>
<P>
During the past decade, the MKO launched a series of attacks on
Iranian interests inside and outside the country. In retaliation,
Iranian air forces also launched several cross-border raids on the
MKO bases near Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
In his talks with the Danish minister, Nouri also accused Israel
of aggression in south Lebanon and the Palestinian lands and
producing and keeping nuclear weapons. Such violations of human
rights should be dealt with seriously, he stressed.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Petersen hailed the expansion of Iran-Denmark
political and economic relations.
</P>
<P>
He added that he believes firmly that Iran's relations with
Denmark and the EU will get stronger in the future, IRNA reported.
</P>
<P>
Peterson arrived here on Tuesday for a two-day visit, during
which he also held talks with his Iranian counterpart Kamal
Kharrazi and Iranian First Vice President Hassan Habibi on
strengthening cooperation in various fields. 
</P>
</TEXT>
