<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Detains Italian Pilot for Violation of Airspace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian aviation authorities on
Wednesday forced a small Italian aircraft to land down at its Azraq
airport, 80 kilometers east of the capital city Amman and detained
its pilot for alleged violation of the Jordanian air space and
civil aviation laws.
</P>
<P>
The P68 plane, piloted by Italian Claudio Castonia and also
carrying four international activists lobbying for the lifting of
U.N. sanctions on Iraq, was believed to have entered the Jordanian
air space from Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The plane was forced down at 0100 pm local time (0200 pm GMT)
Wednesday afternoon by Jordanian aviation officials, who said they
had not been notified by the pilot before his plane entered
Jordanian air space.
</P>
<P>
The small aircraft, which had shuttled between Amman and
Damascus for business missions before the incident, deviated its
routine line on Monday after taking off from Amman, and headed for
Iraq instead of its destination in Syria, Jordanian officials said.
</P>
<P>
The pilot and his passengers were apparently demonstrating their
defiance of an international ban on flights into Iraq, and they
were given a hero's welcome by Iraqi officials after the plane
touched down at an airport in Baghdad on Monday, reports from Iraq
said.
</P>
<P>
The pilot said he had flown his aircraft at a low altitude once
inside Iraq on Monday to avoid radar detection by U.S.-British air
forces, which were policing no-fly zones in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian officials are further investigating the motives of the
pilot and his passengers for the dramatic mission in and out of
Iraq, the first of its kind since U.S. and British forces imposed
no-fly zones in the south and north of Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE20000405.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaraguan Declaration Worries Costa Rica </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SAN JOSE, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Costa Rican authorities reacted
Wednesday with preoccupation before the threats by Nicaraguan
President Arnaldo Aleman of imposing an extraordinary tax on Costa
Rican imports.
</P>
<P>
"We are going to analyze these threats with attention," said
Vice Foreign Trade Minister Anabel Gonzalez. "This sort of actions
violate every Central American integration as well as other
international norms."
</P>
<P>
This would not be the first time Nicaragua's government would
adopt this kind of measures, since it has applied a 35 percent tax
on imports coming from Honduras, as a reprisal for this country's
border limits establishment adoption.
</P>
<P>
The Honduran Congress recently approved a law divining its
maritime border with Colombia in the Caribbean, which Nicaragua
considers as violating its interests.
</P>
<P>
Now Aleman is threatening to adopt a similar measure against
Costa Rica, in case the country decides to take the dispute on
navigation in the border river San Juan to an international court.
</P>
<P>
The two countries held talks last month in the presence of
Cesar Gaviria, secretary general of the Organization of American
States (OAS), in Managua and San Jose respectively, but did not
reach an agreement on the issue.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua, who is enforcing its sovereignty on the river,
opposes the navigation of Costa Rican armed police forces through
that waterway, something which national authorities claim is in
violation of the free navigation right which actual treaties
protect.
</P>
<P>
Costa Rica had announced that, in case the bilateral dialogue
flunk, it would be necessary to access other mechanisms, such as
arbitration or international court.
</P>
<P>
Aleman said Tuesday that if Costa Rica decides to go to an
international tribunal, his country will have to raise taxes to
Costa Rican imports, in order to cover the expenses generated by
this process.
</P>
<P>
Nicaragua is the second trade partner of Costa Rica in Central
America, after Guatemala. Last year, Costa Rican exports to
Nicaragua reached 177 million U.S. dollars, against 25 million U.S.
dollars in imports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
