<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopes for Close Relationship With Japan's New Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. officials said Wednesday
that Washington welcomed Yoshiro Mori to be elected the prime
minister of Japan and hoped to have close working relations with
him.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the Clinton
administration was pleased to see a smooth transition of power in
Japan as Mori was overwhelmingly approved by Japan's parliament to
replace the ailing Keizo Obuchi earlier Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"I think that the administration at all levels is looking
forward to working closely with Prime Minister Mori during this
very difficult period," Lockhart told reporters.
</P>
<P>
When asked about a possible meeting between President Bill
Clinton and Mori, Lockhart declined a positive answer, saying that
he did not know whether they could have any "one-on-one session
like the president has had with some previous Japanese prime
ministers."
</P>
<P>
"But I do think that because of the importance of the
relationship, the president will have an opportunity to speak to
him soon and will have an opportunity to develop a relationship,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin, while "warmly"
welcoming Mori's election by Japan's parliament, said the United
States hoped for a close and cooperative relationship under the
newly-elected Japanese prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"We ... consider Prime Minister Mori to be a strong supporter
of the U.S.-Japan relationship, and look forward to continuing our
close and cooperative relationship with Japan under his leadership,
" he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
