<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Stock Market Shutdown For 8 Hours </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 5 (Xinhua) -- There was chaos in the City of
London Wednesday as unprecedented technical problems halted
trading on one of the London Stock Exchange's busiest days of the
year.
</P>
<P>
The LSE said it had been forced to shut down its information
system, or London Market Information Link, for three hours owing
to technical problems.
</P>
<P>
Investors were outraged by the fault -- the second this week --
which came just hours after violent price swings in U.S. stock
markets where leading indices lurched in ranges as big as 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
The breakdown also coincided with the last day of the tax year
when thousands of investors buy and sell stocks to minimize
capital gains tax liability.
</P>
<P>
City watchdog, the Financial Services Authority, announced an
investigation into the collapse which left millions of investors
unable to trade.
</P>
<P>
In a statement it said, "The FSA sees the failure of major
trading systems to open as a serious matter that requires a prompt
and thorough response."
</P>
<P>
It said it would work with the LSE to examine what changes and
back-up arrangements needed to be made to avoid a repeat of the
debacle. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
