<HEADLINE> Europe's Leading Stocks End in Red </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 5 (Xinhua) - Europe's main stock markets closed
lower Wednesday as many technology, media and telecom shares lost
further ground, mirroring the slides on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
London's FTSE 100 slid to a five week closing low, after a
frustrating day, dominated by a lengthy shutdown caused by a
breakdown in a data feed from the London Stock Exchange. The index
was down 47.70 points, or 0.7 percent, at 6379.3.
</P>
<P>
Germany's Dax share index closed more than two percent lower
but bank shares helped reverse hefty early losses, buoyed by a
sudden collapse of a bank merger between Deutsche Bank and
Dresdner Bank.
</P>
<P>
Insurer Allianz, which would have bought Deutsche's asset
management business and taken a share in the combined personal
banking unit, dropped 13.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Dax index ended at 7330.77 points, down 192.03 or 2.55
percent.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, the benchmark CAC 40 index plunged 185 points, or 2.9
percent, to 6036.94. France Telecom fell 6.2 percent after the
Financial Times reported that the company is eyeing a bid for
British mobile-phone service provider Orange. 
</P>
</TEXT>
