<HEADLINE> Brazil's Airplane Company Gets New Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian Airplane
Company (EMBRAER), Latin America's biggest jet manufacturer,
announced Wednesday that Solitair, Sweden's Solitair AB subsidiary
in the Western Hemisphere, asked a purchase of 90 regional planes
model ERJ-145.
</P>
<P>
EMBRAER's sources said that Solitair, which had acquired 30 ERJ
airplanes on June 1998, presented on Wednesday an order for
another 60 regional airplanes.
</P>
<P>
Orders to Solitair have totaled 90 so far, with a gross value
of 1.5 billion US dollars.
</P>
<P>
With the new orders, the regional airplanes ERJ-135 and ERJ-145
order book is in the order of 1,055 orders, out of which 612 are
firm and 443 are options.
</P>
<P>
This year, until March 31, EMBRAER delivered a total of 225
airplanes to over 25 clients around the world.
</P>
<P>
EMBRAER presented on Wednesday a portfolio of firm and option
orders of its different regional airplane models with a capacity
to transport from 37 to 108 passengers, with a total value above
16.5 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Nowadays, EMBRAER's production chain is making 12 airplanes per
month, and it should reach 16 airplanes per month by December 2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
