<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPRK FM Holds Talks with German Official in Berlin  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
BERLIN, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The Foreign Minister of the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea Paek Nam Sun arrived in
Berlin on Tuesday and had talks with the State Minister of German
Ministry for Foreign Affairs Ludger Volmer on Wednesday in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
Paek Nam Sun was on his way to take part in a meeting of non-
aligned states in Cartagena in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Ludger Volmer expressed his "deep concern" over possible
development of weapons of mass destruction and the already
successful test of missile delivery systems of the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea.
</P>
<P>
He called on Paek Nam Sun to open direct dialogue with its
southern neighboring country without any preconditions.
</P>
<P>
Volmer stressed that disarmament was the key to security on
the Korean peninsula and the Democratic People's Republic of Korea
could contribute to the stability on the Korean peninsula through
its disarmament, nuclear non-proliferation and acceding to the
treaty for nuclear test ban.
</P>
<P>
Paek stressed also that now the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea is not going to develop the atomic weapons, but
possession of guided missile is a right of every state.
</P>
<P>
Paek's visit to Germany is the first high-level diplomatic
contact between the Democratic People's Republic of Korea and
Germany since the 1980s. The Democratic People's Republic of Korea
kept the diplomatic relations with the former German Democratic
Republic in the past. After Germany's reunification in 1990 the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea had not established
diplomatic relations with reunified Germany.
</P>
<P>
The Democratic People's Republic of Korea remained an agency
of rights and interests in Berlin after Germany's reunification.
The embassy of the People's Republic of China in Berlin is in
charge of rights and interests of the Democratic People's Republic
of Korea in Germany. The Swedish embassy in Pyongyang is in charge
of Germany's rights and interests.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement of the German Ministry for Foreign
Affairs there is no any reason to refuse a talk on the level
because the European Union had resumed a dialogue with the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea. The Italian Foreign
Minister Lamberto Dini had visited Pyongyang on March 27.
</P>
<P>
"The German government currently has no intention of changing
the status of bilateral relations," said the statement of the
German Foreign Ministry. Germany will still provide with further
aids for the Democratic People's Republic of Korea. Last year
Germany had given the Democratic People's Republic of Korea 3.6
million marks (1.8 million dollars) worth humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
For the last time a official delegation with a member of the
Political Bureau of the Labour Party of the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea had visited the former Federal Republic of
Germany at the beginning of 1980s. At that time the delegation was
received by the member of the presidium of the German Social
Democratic Party (SPD) Erhard Eppler and the politician for the
foreign policy of the German Liberal Democratic Party Juergen
Moellemann. 
</P>
</TEXT>
