<HEADLINE> Over 3 Million Ethiopians Suffer River Blindness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, April 5 (Xinhua) -- More than three million people
in Ethiopia are suffering river blindness, a bacterial disease
transmitted by flies hatched in rivers, an expert of the Health
Ministry said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Desta Alamirew, malaria and vector borne disease expert, said
that river blindness causes painful skin irritation and leads some
people to go blind.
</P>
<P>
People living along river banks are particularly prone to the
disease, he said, noting that the disease is rampant in many areas
down along the northwest-southwest escarpment.
</P>
<P>
The Health Ministry is preparing to conduct an inclusive study
on the distribution and frequency of the disease, and has designed
a five-year program to curb the disease at the reported areas,
Desta added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
