<HEADLINE> Albania Urged to Cooperate in Fighting Organized Crime </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
ATHENS, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Greece Wednesday night urged
neighboring Albania to cooperate in combating the increasingly
organized crime.
</P>
<P>
Expressing Greece's concern over the inability of Albanian
authorities to curb organized crime and guard the marine and land
borders of their country, Greek Foreign Ministry spokesman
Panagiotis Beglitis hoped that Albanian authorities would
cooperate with their Greek counterparts to curb illegal activities
and put an end to incidents, such as those of the past days when
migrant traffickers attempted to land on the western Greek island
of Corfu.
</P>
<P>
Beglitis said that Greece respected the rules of international
law and international agreements which govern relations between
states, and it was also at the forefront of initiatives which are
aimed at cooperation, security, peaceful co-existence and economic
development of Balkan countries.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, a large quantity of illegal immigrants have
entered Greece with the aim of seeking a better life, and some of
them have been blamed by Greeks for the increasing crime in Greece.
</P>
</TEXT>
