<HEADLINE> Tech Stocks Bounce Back After Panic Selling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, April 5 (Xinhua) -- The technology stocks bounced
back Wednesday after a  panic selling in the previous session,
lifting the Nasdaq composite higher. But blue chip stocks
continued to fall.
</P>
<P>
At the close of session, the technology heavy Nasdaq composite
index rose 20.33 at 4,169.22.
</P>
<P>
Early in the session, the Nasdaq index fell as much as 139.80
points as investors continued to pull money out the market
following the panic selling in the previous session. The index
dropped 574.57 points in the midday and closed down 74.79 points
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Investors moved cautiously back into the market for bargain-
hunting in the later session today, driving the Nasdaq index into
the positive territory.
</P>
<P>
Tech stocks were supported by remarks from the Federal Reserve
chairman Alan Greenspan. Addressing a gathering of top economist
and corporate executives assembled by U.S. president Bill Clinton
in the White House today, Greenspan said "extraordinary surge in
technological innovation" created the current record-breaking
economy in the United States.
</P>
<P>
But the Dow Jones industrial average fell 130.92 at 11,033.92,
after giving up an early gain. The Dow index fell as much as 503.
53 points during the session and closed down 57.09 points Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index fell 7.36 at 1,487.37
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 1.77 at 650.53. The American Stock Exchange
index rose 14.19 at 956.71 and the Russell 2000 index of smaller
companies rose 11.92 at 518.04.
</P>
<P>
Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 9-to-7 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,694 up, 1,328 down and 445
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume declined to 1.12 billion shares from 1.50 billion
in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
