<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian President to Visit Bosnia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 5 (Xinhua) -- Italian President Carlo Azeglio
Ciampi is scheduled to arrive in Sarajevo on Thursday in the midst
of tensions generated by Russia's anger over the capture of an
indicted Serb war criminal by French troops in NATO-led forces in
Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Russian Foreign Ministry said the arrest of
Momcilo Krajisnik, a former Bosnian Serb official, and transport
to the Hague for trial before the United Nations International
Criminal Tribunal for former Yugoslavia marked "a clear violation
of legal regulations."
</P>
<P>
Ciampi said Wednesday that he wanted to see all countries
involved in the crisis-ridden Balkans to "examine their
consciences" as to why progress on Balkan problems is "lacking or
insufficient".
</P>
<P>
He also urged European Union to have the courage and
imagination to take responsibility for resolve regional crisis.
</P>
<P>
During his stay, Ciampi will also go to the Tito Barracks in
Sarajevo to pay his respects to the more than 1,600 Italian troops
committed to the NATO-led peacekeeping operations in Bosnia.
</P>
</TEXT>
